del teatro 2018/2019\"], ''[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clarin]]'', Buenos Aires, 5 August 2019. Retrieved 16 March 2020.</ref><ref>[https://www.ciudad.com.ar/espectaculos/blooper-premios-ace-anunciarse-ganador-oro-todos-ganadores-no-hay-nada-escrito_126464 \"El blooper en los Premios ACE al anunciarse el ganador del Oro y todos los ganadores: \"No hay nada escrito\"\"], ''[[:es:Ciudad Magazine|Ciudad Magazine]]'', Buenos Aires, 6 November 2019. Retrieved 16 March 2020.</ref>\n| ''N\u00fcremberg''\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|4980387}}\n*[http://www.alternativateatral.com/persona108443-mateo-chiarino Alternativa Teatral: Mateo Chiarino-Actor]\n*[https://www.alejandrovannelli.com.ar/mateo-chiarino?lang=en Alejandro Vannelli: Mateo Chiarino]\n*[https://www.dailymotion.com/video/x3807y2 radiolexa: \"EL SUBE Y BAJA con Mateo Chiarino\"]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/282088385227185/posts/1818604778242197/ Grandes de la Escena Nacional: \"Nueva Generaci\u00f3n: MATEO CHIARINO\"]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chiarino, Mateo}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan people stubs]]\n[[Category:People from Montevideo]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Montevideo]]\n[[Category:21st-century Uruguayan male actors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan actors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan male actors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan film actors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan male film actors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan male television actors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan film directors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Uruguayan screenwriters]]\n[[Category:South American actor stubs]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Uruguayan descent]]\n", "name_user": "Slucas", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTheatre:re-ordered", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mateo_Chiarino"}
{"title_page": "Nissan NX", "text_new": "{{Not to be confused with|Lexus NX}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|image=Nissan 100NX.JPG\n|caption=Nissan 100NX 1.6 T-bar roof in The Netherlands.\n|name=Nissan NX\n|manufacturer=[[Nissan]]\n|class=[[Sports car]]\n|production=1990\u20131996\n|body_style=2-door [[coup\u00e9]]<br />2-door [[Targa top]]\n|engine={{unbulleted list|1.5&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan GA engine#GA15DS|GA15DS]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (JDM only)|1.6&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan GA engine#GA16DS|GA16DS]]/[[Nissan GA engine#GA16DE|DE]]'' I4|1.8&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan SR engine#SR18DE|SR18DE]]'' I4 (JDM only)|2.0&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan SR engine#SR20DE|SR20DE]]'' I4}}\n|platform=[[Nissan B platform]]\n|layout=[[FF layout]]\n|wheelbase= {{convert|95.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|length= {{convert|162.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|width= {{convert|66.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|height= {{convert|50.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|weight= {{convert|2248|-|2513|lb|abbr=on}}\n|transmission={{unbulleted list|4-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]| \n5-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]}}\n|predecessor={{unbulleted list|[[Nissan EXA|Nissan Pulsar NX/EXA]]|[[Nissan Sunny#Sunny RZ-1 Series FB12 (1986-1989)|Nissan Sunny Coupe]]}}\n|successor={{unbulleted list|[[Nissan 200SX]] (North America)|[[Nissan Lucino]] (Japan)}}\n|related={{unbulleted list|[[Nissan Sentra]]|[[Nissan Sunny]]|[[Nissan Pulsar]]}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Nissan NX''' is a front wheel drive 2-door sports [[car]] produced by [[Nissan Motors]]. The NX was, loosely, an evolution of the [[Nissan EXA|Nissan Pulsar NX/Nissan EXA]] sold from 1987\u20131990 and the Nissan Sunny Coupe lines of the 1970s and 1980s, merging the Nissan B13 and N14 lineages. The NX was released in Japan in 1990.\n\n==Models==\n===NX1600/NX2000 (North America)===\nThe NX1600 was based on the standard 1.6-litre [[Nissan Sentra|Sentra]] (engine code GA16DE), and the NX2000 was based on the 2.0&nbsp;L SE-R model (engine code SR20DE). Most models were fitted with T-Tops, whilst the remainder were hardtops. Constructed in Japan, it was sold from 1991\u20131993 in the [[United States|US]] (mainly competing with the [[Mazda MX-3]], [[Isuzu Piazza#1990\u20131992 (1990\u20131991 and 1993 in Canada)|Isuzu Piazza]], [[Toyota MR2]], and [[Honda Civic Del Sol]]). It was produced for a few more years for other countries. Its body was designed at NDI (Nissan Design International) in San Diego under the direction of NDI President Jerry Hirshberg, Blue Studio Chief Designer Allan Flowers, and staff designers Bruce Campbell and Doug Wilson.\n\nThe NX2000 model included some mechanical improvements over its SE-R sibling in the form of larger brakes and more aggressive tires on wider 6\" wheels (195/55VR-14 with 14x6\" wheels vs. the 185/60HR-14 with 14x5.5\" wheels and tires in the SE-R). The NX2000 brakes are a common aftermarket upgrade for B13 Sentra SE-Rs. The NX2000 also had a center armrest, a larger two-core radiator, and slightly lower ride height compared to the SE-R. However, the T-top roof in the NX2000 along with the mechanical upgrades made it slightly heavier than the SE-R.\n\nThe NX2000, with its light weight, stiff chassis, and limited-slip differential, was considered one of the best-handling front-wheel-drive cars of the time. In 1992, [[Road & Track]] magazine included the NX2000 in a test of the world's best-handling cars against such competition as the [[Acura NSX]], [[Porsche 911]], [[Nissan 300ZX]], [[Mazda Miata]], and [[Lotus Elan]].\n\n===100NX (Europe)===\n[[File:Nissan 100NX 2.0 16V T-bar, rear left.jpg|thumb|Rear view of a Nissan 100NX 2.0 16V T-bar (Germany)]]\nThe 100NX came with two engine options, a 1.6&nbsp;L and a 2.0&nbsp;L.\n\nThe 1.6&nbsp;liter, made from 1990 to February 1993 had a [[carburetor]] fitted which tended to consume excessive fuel as it aged. From April 1993 to 1996, the 100NX was sold with a more efficient [[fuel injected]] setup. In November 1993 a version called the SR appeared. This stands for \"Steel Roof\" as this slightly sportier model was lighter and more rigid. The SR's engine produced somewhat more power than the regular GA16DS thanks to a modified control unit and an enlarged intake manifold. The gearing was also shorter than for the regular 1.6.\n\n*1.6 with ECU carbureted \u2014 {{convert|90|PS|kW hp|0|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 Non ECU carbureted \u2014 {{convert|95|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|90|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|102|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} SR model\n*2.0 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|140|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} North American version\n*2.0 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|143|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\nThe 1.6&nbsp;liter fuel injected version achieved {{convert|0|-|60|mph|abbr=on}} in 10.5 seconds and had a top speed of {{convert|121|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe 100NX was mainly sold with a T-bar removable roof in Europe although this does vary from country to country. Specialised Badged Editions sold only in 1995 include the \"Pacific\" in Ireland and the United Kingdom and the \"Sail\" in the Netherlands. Features vary from country to country, such features include heated seats, electric windows, other differences although rarer include cup holders, umbrella holder embedded in the driver's side B-pillar, and headlight wipers.\n\n===100NX (UK)===\n\nThe Nissan 100NX was initially introduced in the UK in April 1991 as part of the [[Nissan Pulsar]] range replacing the [[Nissan Sunny]] 1.6 GSX Coupe. At this time Nissan UK, the British importer were in a heated dispute with [[Nissan Motor Corporation]] over profit margins. In an attempt to deliberately shrink market share Nissan UK launched the entire Pulsar range with no promotion as well as only providing a limited colour range and pricing all models well above their position in the market. At launch the 100NX was only available with the 1.6L 95&nbsp;PS carburetor engine, and in a basic specification, priced at \u00a314,585, the same price as a 2.0&nbsp;L [[Toyota MR2]] and \u00a31,000 more than the 2.0L [[Honda Prelude]]. T-bar roof and automatic transmission were optional. In January 1992 Nissan Motor Corporation set up their own importer (Nissan Motor (GB) LTD) and relaunched the entire Nissan Range, the 100NX now coming with alloy wheels, T-bar roof and front foglights as standard at a lower price of \u00a311,817 and was available in a full range of colours.\n\nFrom February 1993 to 1996, the 100NX the carburetor engine was replaced by a more efficient [[fuel injected]] setup.\n\n*1.6 Non-ECU carbureted \u2014 {{convert|89|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|101|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}\n\n===NX Coup\u00e9 (Japan)===\nThe Nissan NX was also sold in the Japanese domestic market as the Nissan NX Coup\u00e9. Some models were fitted with T-Tops, whilst others were hardtop. The Japanese domestic NX Coup\u00e9s came with either a 1.5 [[DOHC]] carburetted engine (GA15(DS)), a 1.6 DOHC EFI engine (GA16(DE)), a 1.8 DOHC EFI engine (SR18(DE)) or the rare 2.0 DOHC EFI engine (SR20DE). The model was available in automatic or manual transmission. The 1.5 DOHC models were all fitted with digital speedometers, whilst all other engine versions had the standard analogue gage. All Japanese domestic models were fitted with electric windows, [[air conditioning]], power steering, electric mirrors and central locking which locked the doors automatically at 18&nbsp;km/h whilst driving, and was exclusive to ''[[Nissan Motor Company#Japan|Nissan Cherry Store]]'' Japanese dealerships.\n\n===NX Coup\u00e9/NX-R (Australia)===\n[[File:1993 Nissan NX (B13) R coupe (2003-02-01) 02.jpg|thumb|left|Interior]]\n[[File:1994 Nissan NX (B13) R coupe (2016-01-04) 02.jpg|thumb|Nissan NX-R (B13) in Australia.]]\nThe Nissan NX was also sold in the Australian market as the Nissan NX Coup\u00e9. A range topping model known as the NX-R included an added front lip with fog/driving lights, side skirts, lip rear spoiler, 14\" Alloy Wheels (N14 SSS Pulsar), cruise control, leather steering wheel and gear knob, electric windows and ABS (Anti-lock Braking System). Both models were only ever offered with the powerful 105&nbsp;kW/178Nm 2.0L naturally aspirated inline 4 cylinder engine (SR20DE). The NX also came with a choice between a smooth 4-speed automatic gearbox or a sporty 5-speed manual. Unfortunately, no LSD (Limited Slip Differential) was offered in Australia for the NX range. It has a claimed 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (62 mph) acceleration time of 8.2 seconds<ref>https://www.autoevolution.com/cars/nissan-100-nx-1991.html#aeng_nissan-100-nx-1990-20-gti</ref> and with a combined fuel consumption figure of just 8.4L/100&nbsp;km would be considered above average.\n\n==Safety==\nIn [[Australia]], the 1991-96 Nissan NX was assessed in the Used Car Safety Ratings 2006 as providing \"significantly worse than average\" protection for its occupants in the event of a crash.<ref>[http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/vrne/vrne5nav.nsf/childdocs/-B8F8655488907260CA256FD300241C1A-667BCFE41674A389CA256FD300241C2B-1EE471300C4801C3CA2570A400083B3F?open ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519194933/http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/vrne/vrne5nav.nsf/childdocs/-B8F8655488907260CA256FD300241C1A-667BCFE41674A389CA256FD300241C2B-1EE471300C4801C3CA2570A400083B3F?open |date=May 19, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Racing==\n\n===Land speed records===\n;2011: Reg Cook Motor Sport set a new Class G/ Pro world record land speed class record at Bonneville speed week of 279.24 km/h (174.525 mph), using a Nissan NX Coupe 1999 cc SR 20 Eng\n\n===North America===\n\n====SCCA Showroom Stock B====\n\nSoon after its import into the United States, the NX2000 was classified by the Sports Car Club of America ([[SCCA]]) into its Showroom Stock B category for the 1992 year, pitting it against such cars as [[Mitsubishi Mirage]] Turbo (defending SSB champion Gerald Alaimo and others), its B13 cousin the [[Nissan Sentra]] SE-R (David Daughtery and others), and the sole second-generation [[Toyota MR2]] (driven by Dane Pitaressi). The NX2000 posted several National wins throughout the year, and garnered much attention from competitors. The 1992 SSB SCCA Runoffs championships saw two podium finishes for the NX2000, with the gold medal taken home by Mark Youngquist, followed by Ken Payson in a Mirage, then Greg Amy in his NX2000 taking home third place.\n\nThe 1993 season proved it wasn't a fluke, as David Daughtery took home yet another SCCA Runoffs championship for the NX2000. However, by that time the 1993 MR-2 with its updated suspension and the much-improved S14 version of the [[Nissan 240SX]] came along; while the NX2000 continued to be campaigned nationally, and sporadically posted wins throughout subsequent racing seasons, it never again won a Runoffs championship (Tony Suever won in '94 with the MR-2, and the '95 and '96 SSB championships were won by Daughtery in the S14 240SXh.<ref>http://www.nissannews.com/site_library/events/nissan/motorsport/2002/sccachampions.doc</ref>) The car timed out for eligibility for SSB racing soon thereafter.\n\n====SCCA Improved Touring====\nThe Nissan NX2000 and the Sentra SE-R were soon approved for SCCA's [[Improved Touring]] category. At the time of its initial classification - due primarily to their larger (2.0-liter) displacement - they were dropped into the ITS, or Sports, class. This pitted them against other larger-displacement, GT-class cars such as the Mazda RX-7 and BMW 325. The cars languished in ITS for several years; despite a few sporadic oddball wins in ITS (\"Crazy Joe\" DiMinno in his Sentra SE-R at [[Watkins Glen International]] in the rain in 2003) due to its very low chances of winning it garnered very little interest from competitors. Further, despite numerous requests from SCCA competitors it was never re-classified into a lower class (such as ITA, with the Acura Integra, Honda CRX Si, [[Saturn SC]], etc.).\n\nIn 2001, Kakashi Racing from [[Connecticut]] began to prepare both a Nissan NX2000 for former SSB driver Greg Amy and provide support for DiMinno in his Sentra (the NX of Greg Amy was the same chassis he used in the '92 Runoffs). At the same time they began an effort to convince SCCA that the car belonged in ITA. They coordinated efforts with Kirk Knestis to form a sub-group called \"Improved Touring 2\" to bring attention to the \"orphaned\" 2-liter front-wheel-drive cars languishing in ITS. In 2004 SCCA announced a complete re-vamp of the IT classification process, placing both Nissan B13 cars into ITA for the 2005 racing season. The end result was a 2006 [[American Road Race of Champions]] (ARRC) ITA win at [[Road Atlanta]] for Greg Amy and Kakashi Racing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arrc-online.com/results_2006/2006ARRC_Grp4RACE.pdf |format=PDF |title=Temporarily Disabled |publisher=Arrc-online.com |date=2008-07-10 |accessdate=2009-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723120501/http://www.arrc-online.com/results_2006/2006ARRC_Grp4RACE.pdf |archivedate=July 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nDue to this success the car has again garnered a lot of attention from competitors, and a resurgence of entries for both the NX2000 and Sentra SE-R in Improved Touring is expected.\n\n====Professional Race Series====\n* 1991: Richard Laporte and others. [[Firestone Firehawk Endurance Championship]] class T, 5th overall.<ref>[http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/national/firehawk/1991/firehawk.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060302124353/http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/national/firehawk/1991/firehawk.htm |date=March 2, 2006 }}</ref>\n* 1992: Richard Laporte, Pierre Desmarais and others. Firestone Firehawk Endurance Championship class T, 3rd and 4th overall.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/national/firehawk/1992/firehawk.htm</ref>\n* 1993: Mark Youngquist. World Challenge C, Sentra SE-R, 9th overall final standings.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/usa/wc/1993/wc.htm</ref>\n* 1994: Thomas Thorman, Jose Luis Pombo. SCCA World Challenge World Challenge Super Production.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/usa/wc/1994/wc.htm</ref>\n* 1995: Thomas Thorman. SCCA World Challenge World Challenge Super Production.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/usa/wc/1995/wc.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{nissan}}\n{{Modern North American Nissan vehicles}}\n{{Modern European Nissan vehicles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nissan Nx}}\n[[Category:Nissan vehicles|NX]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive sports cars]]\n[[Category:Sport compact cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1990]]\n", "text_old": "{{Not to be confused with|Lexus NX}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|image=Nissan 100NX.JPG\n|caption=Nissan 100NX 1.6 T-bar roof in The Netherlands.\n|name=Nissan NX\n|manufacturer=[[Nissan]]\n|class=[[Sports car]]\n|production=1990\u20131996\n|body_style=2-door [[coup\u00e9]]<br />2-door [[Targa top]]\n|engine={{unbulleted list|1.5&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan GA engine#GA15DS|GA15DS]]'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] (JDM only)|1.6&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan GA engine#GA16DS|GA16DS]]/[[Nissan GA engine#GA16DE|DE]]'' I4|1.8&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan SR engine#SR18DE|SR18DE]]'' I4 (JDM only)|2.0&nbsp;L ''[[Nissan SR engine#SR20DE|SR20DE]]'' I4}}\n|platform=[[Nissan B platform]]\n|layout=[[FF layout]]\n|wheelbase= {{convert|95.7|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|length= {{convert|162.4|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|width= {{convert|66.1|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|height= {{convert|50.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|weight= {{convert|2248|-|2513|lb|abbr=on}}\n|transmission={{unbulleted list|4-speed [[automatic transmission|automatic]]| \n5-speed [[manual transmission|manual]]}}\n|predecessor={{unbulleted list|[[Nissan EXA|Nissan Pulsar NX/EXA]]|[[Nissan Sunny#Sunny RZ-1 Series FB12 (1986-1989)|Nissan Sunny Coupe]]}}\n|successor={{unbulleted list|[[Nissan 200SX]] (North America)|[[Nissan Lucino]] (Japan)}}\n|related={{unbulleted list|[[Nissan Sentra]]|[[Nissan Sunny]]|[[Nissan Pulsar]]}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Nissan NX''' is a front wheel drive 2-door sports [[car]] produced by [[Nissan Motors]]. The NX was, loosely, an evolution of the [[Nissan EXA|Nissan Pulsar NX/Nissan EXA]] sold from 1987\u20131990 and the Nissan Sunny Coupe lines of the 1970s and 1980s, merging the Nissan B13 and N14 lineages. The NX was released in Japan in 1990.\n\n==Models==\n===NX1600/NX2000 (North America)===\nThe NX1600 was based on the standard 1.6-litre [[Nissan Sentra|Sentra]] (engine code GA16DE), and the NX2000 was based on the 2.0&nbsp;L SE-R model (engine code SR20DE). Most models were fitted with T-Tops, whilst the remainder were hardtops. Constructed in Japan, it was sold from 1991-1993 in the [[United States|US]] (mainly competing with the [[Mazda MX-3]], [[Isuzu Piazza#1990\u20131992 (1990\u20131991 and 1993 in Canada)|Isuzu Piazza]], [[Toyota MR2]], and [[Honda Civic Del Sol]]). It was produced for a few more years for other countries. Its body was designed at NDI (Nissan Design International) in San Diego under the direction of NDI President Jerry Hirshberg, Blue Studio Chief Designer Allan Flowers, and staff designers Bruce Campbell and Doug Wilson.\n\nThe NX2000 model included some mechanical improvements over its SE-R sibling in the form of larger brakes and more aggressive tires on wider 6\" wheels (195/55VR-14 with 14x6\" wheels vs. the 185/60HR-14 with 14x5.5\" wheels and tires in the SE-R). The NX2000 brakes are a common aftermarket upgrade for B13 Sentra SE-Rs. The NX2000 also had a center armrest, a larger two-core radiator, and slightly lower ride height compared to the SE-R. However, the T-top roof in the NX2000 along with the mechanical upgrades made it slightly heavier than the SE-R.\n\nThe NX2000, with its light weight, stiff chassis, and limited-slip differential, was considered one of the best-handling front-wheel-drive cars of the time. In 1992, [[Road & Track]] magazine included the NX2000 in a test of the world's best-handling cars against such competition as the [[Acura NSX]], [[Porsche 911]], [[Nissan 300ZX]], [[Mazda Miata]], and [[Lotus Elan]].\n\n===100NX (Europe)===\n[[File:Nissan 100NX 2.0 16V T-bar, rear left.jpg|thumb|Rear view of a Nissan 100NX 2.0 16V T-bar (Germany)]]\nThe 100NX came with two engine options, a 1.6&nbsp;L and a 2.0&nbsp;L.\n\nThe 1.6&nbsp;liter, made from 1990 to February 1993 had a [[carburetor]] fitted which tended to consume excessive fuel as it aged. From April 1993 to 1996, the 100NX was sold with a more efficient [[fuel injected]] setup. In November 1993 a version called the SR appeared. This stands for \"Steel Roof\" as this slightly sportier model was lighter and more rigid. The SR's engine produced somewhat more power than the regular GA16DS thanks to a modified control unit and an enlarged intake manifold. The gearing was also shorter than for the regular 1.6.\n\n*1.6 with ECU carbureted \u2014 {{convert|90|PS|kW hp|0|lk=in|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 Non ECU carbureted \u2014 {{convert|95|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|90|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|102|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} SR model\n*2.0 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|140|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} North American version\n*2.0 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|143|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}}\nThe 1.6&nbsp;liter fuel injected version achieved {{convert|0|-|60|mph|abbr=on}} in 10.5 seconds and had a top speed of {{convert|121|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe 100NX was mainly sold with a T-bar removable roof in Europe although this does vary from country to country. Specialised Badged Editions sold only in 1995 include the \"Pacific\" in Ireland and the United Kingdom and the \"Sail\" in the Netherlands. Features vary from country to country, such features include heated seats, electric windows, other differences although rarer include cup holders, umbrella holder embedded in the driver's side B-pillar, and headlight wipers.\n\n===100NX (UK)===\n\nThe Nissan 100NX was initially introduced in the UK in April 1991 as part of the [[Nissan Pulsar]] range replacing the [[Nissan Sunny]] 1.6 GSX Coupe. At this time Nissan UK, the British importer were in a heated dispute with [[Nissan Motor Corporation]] over profit margins. In an attempt to deliberately shrink market share Nissan UK launched the entire Pulsar range with no promotion as well as only providing a limited colour range and pricing all models well above their position in the market. At launch the 100NX was only available with the 1.6L 95&nbsp;PS carburetor engine, and in a basic specification, priced at \u00a314,585, the same price as a 2.0&nbsp;L [[Toyota MR2]] and \u00a31,000 more than the 2.0L [[Honda Prelude]]. T-bar roof and automatic transmission were optional. In January 1992 Nissan Motor Corporation set up their own importer (Nissan Motor (GB) LTD) and relaunched the entire Nissan Range, the 100NX now coming with alloy wheels, T-bar roof and front foglights as standard at a lower price of \u00a311,817 and was available in a full range of colours.\n\nFrom February 1993 to 1996, the 100NX the carburetor engine was replaced by a more efficient [[fuel injected]] setup.\n\n*1.6 Non-ECU carbureted \u2014 {{convert|89|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}\n*1.6 fuel injected \u2014 {{convert|101|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}}\n\n===NX Coup\u00e9 (Japan)===\nThe Nissan NX was also sold in the Japanese domestic market as the Nissan NX Coup\u00e9. Some models were fitted with T-Tops, whilst others were hardtop. The Japanese domestic NX Coup\u00e9s came with either a 1.5 [[DOHC]] carburetted engine (GA15(DS)), a 1.6 DOHC EFI engine (GA16(DE)), a 1.8 DOHC EFI engine (SR18(DE)) or the rare 2.0 DOHC EFI engine (SR20DE). The model was available in automatic or manual transmission. The 1.5 DOHC models were all fitted with digital speedometers, whilst all other engine versions had the standard analogue gage. All Japanese domestic models were fitted with electric windows, [[air conditioning]], power steering, electric mirrors and central locking which locked the doors automatically at 18&nbsp;km/h whilst driving, and was exclusive to ''[[Nissan Motor Company#Japan|Nissan Cherry Store]]'' Japanese dealerships.\n\n===NX Coup\u00e9/NX-R (Australia)===\n[[File:1993 Nissan NX (B13) R coupe (2003-02-01) 02.jpg|thumb|left|Interior]]\n[[File:1994 Nissan NX (B13) R coupe (2016-01-04) 02.jpg|thumb|Nissan NX-R (B13) in Australia.]]\nThe Nissan NX was also sold in the Australian market as the Nissan NX Coup\u00e9. A range topping model known as the NX-R included an added front lip with fog/driving lights, side skirts, lip rear spoiler, 14\" Alloy Wheels (N14 SSS Pulsar), cruise control, leather steering wheel and gear knob, electric windows and ABS (Anti-lock Braking System). Both models were only ever offered with the powerful 105&nbsp;kW/178Nm 2.0L naturally aspirated inline 4 cylinder engine (SR20DE). The NX also came with a choice between a smooth 4-speed automatic gearbox or a sporty 5-speed manual. Unfortunately, no LSD (Limited Slip Differential) was offered in Australia for the NX range. It has a claimed 0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (62 mph) acceleration time of 8.2 seconds<ref>https://www.autoevolution.com/cars/nissan-100-nx-1991.html#aeng_nissan-100-nx-1990-20-gti</ref> and with a combined fuel consumption figure of just 8.4L/100&nbsp;km would be considered above average.\n\n==Safety==\nIn [[Australia]], the 1991-96 Nissan NX was assessed in the Used Car Safety Ratings 2006 as providing \"significantly worse than average\" protection for its occupants in the event of a crash.<ref>[http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/vrne/vrne5nav.nsf/childdocs/-B8F8655488907260CA256FD300241C1A-667BCFE41674A389CA256FD300241C2B-1EE471300C4801C3CA2570A400083B3F?open ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519194933/http://www.vicroads.vic.gov.au/vrne/vrne5nav.nsf/childdocs/-B8F8655488907260CA256FD300241C1A-667BCFE41674A389CA256FD300241C2B-1EE471300C4801C3CA2570A400083B3F?open |date=May 19, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Racing==\n\n===Land speed records===\n;2011: Reg Cook Motor Sport set a new Class G/ Pro world record land speed class record at Bonneville speed week of 279.24 km/h (174.525 mph), using a Nissan NX Coupe 1999 cc SR 20 Eng\n\n===North America===\n\n====SCCA Showroom Stock B====\n\nSoon after its import into the United States, the NX2000 was classified by the Sports Car Club of America ([[SCCA]]) into its Showroom Stock B category for the 1992 year, pitting it against such cars as [[Mitsubishi Mirage]] Turbo (defending SSB champion Gerald Alaimo and others), its B13 cousin the [[Nissan Sentra]] SE-R (David Daughtery and others), and the sole second-generation [[Toyota MR2]] (driven by Dane Pitaressi). The NX2000 posted several National wins throughout the year, and garnered much attention from competitors. The 1992 SSB SCCA Runoffs championships saw two podium finishes for the NX2000, with the gold medal taken home by Mark Youngquist, followed by Ken Payson in a Mirage, then Greg Amy in his NX2000 taking home third place.\n\nThe 1993 season proved it wasn't a fluke, as David Daughtery took home yet another SCCA Runoffs championship for the NX2000. However, by that time the 1993 MR-2 with its updated suspension and the much-improved S14 version of the [[Nissan 240SX]] came along; while the NX2000 continued to be campaigned nationally, and sporadically posted wins throughout subsequent racing seasons, it never again won a Runoffs championship (Tony Suever won in '94 with the MR-2, and the '95 and '96 SSB championships were won by Daughtery in the S14 240SXh.<ref>http://www.nissannews.com/site_library/events/nissan/motorsport/2002/sccachampions.doc</ref>) The car timed out for eligibility for SSB racing soon thereafter.\n\n====SCCA Improved Touring====\nThe Nissan NX2000 and the Sentra SE-R were soon approved for SCCA's [[Improved Touring]] category. At the time of its initial classification - due primarily to their larger (2.0-liter) displacement - they were dropped into the ITS, or Sports, class. This pitted them against other larger-displacement, GT-class cars such as the Mazda RX-7 and BMW 325. The cars languished in ITS for several years; despite a few sporadic oddball wins in ITS (\"Crazy Joe\" DiMinno in his Sentra SE-R at [[Watkins Glen International]] in the rain in 2003) due to its very low chances of winning it garnered very little interest from competitors. Further, despite numerous requests from SCCA competitors it was never re-classified into a lower class (such as ITA, with the Acura Integra, Honda CRX Si, [[Saturn SC]], etc.).\n\nIn 2001, Kakashi Racing from [[Connecticut]] began to prepare both a Nissan NX2000 for former SSB driver Greg Amy and provide support for DiMinno in his Sentra (the NX of Greg Amy was the same chassis he used in the '92 Runoffs). At the same time they began an effort to convince SCCA that the car belonged in ITA. They coordinated efforts with Kirk Knestis to form a sub-group called \"Improved Touring 2\" to bring attention to the \"orphaned\" 2-liter front-wheel-drive cars languishing in ITS. In 2004 SCCA announced a complete re-vamp of the IT classification process, placing both Nissan B13 cars into ITA for the 2005 racing season. The end result was a 2006 [[American Road Race of Champions]] (ARRC) ITA win at [[Road Atlanta]] for Greg Amy and Kakashi Racing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arrc-online.com/results_2006/2006ARRC_Grp4RACE.pdf |format=PDF |title=Temporarily Disabled |publisher=Arrc-online.com |date=2008-07-10 |accessdate=2009-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723120501/http://www.arrc-online.com/results_2006/2006ARRC_Grp4RACE.pdf |archivedate=July 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nDue to this success the car has again garnered a lot of attention from competitors, and a resurgence of entries for both the NX2000 and Sentra SE-R in Improved Touring is expected.\n\n====Professional Race Series====\n* 1991: Richard Laporte and others. [[Firestone Firehawk Endurance Championship]] class T, 5th overall.<ref>[http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/national/firehawk/1991/firehawk.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060302124353/http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/national/firehawk/1991/firehawk.htm |date=March 2, 2006 }}</ref>\n* 1992: Richard Laporte, Pierre Desmarais and others. Firestone Firehawk Endurance Championship class T, 3rd and 4th overall.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/national/firehawk/1992/firehawk.htm</ref>\n* 1993: Mark Youngquist. World Challenge C, Sentra SE-R, 9th overall final standings.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/usa/wc/1993/wc.htm</ref>\n* 1994: Thomas Thorman, Jose Luis Pombo. SCCA World Challenge World Challenge Super Production.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/usa/wc/1994/wc.htm</ref>\n* 1995: Thomas Thorman. SCCA World Challenge World Challenge Super Production.<ref>http://www.autocourse.ca/archives/usa/wc/1995/wc.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{nissan}}\n{{Modern North American Nissan vehicles}}\n{{Modern European Nissan vehicles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nissan Nx}}\n[[Category:Nissan vehicles|NX]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive sports cars]]\n[[Category:Sport compact cars]]\n[[Category:1990s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1990]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNX1600/NX2000 (North America):Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1991-1993 \u2192 1991\u20131993", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nissan_NX"}
{"title_page": "Santa Costanza", "text_new": "[[Image:Santa Costanza - vista dalla basilica costantiniana.jpg|thumb|upright= 1.5|View of the mausoleum of Santa Costanza and the remaining wall of the Constantinian basilica (photo taken from its apse).]] \n[[File:Piranesi-2023.jpg|thumb|upright= 1.5|[[giovanni Battista Piranesi|Piranesi's]] etching of the elevations of the site]]\n'''Santa Costanza''' is a 4th-century church in [[Rome]], Italy, on the [[Via Nomentana]], which runs north-east out of the city. It is a round building with well preserved original layout and mosaics. It has been built adjacent to a horseshoe-shaped church, now in ruins, which has been identified as the initial 4th-century cemeterial [[basilica]] of [[Saint Agnes]]. (Note that the much later [[Sant'Agnese fuori le mura|Church of St Agnes]], still standing nearby, is distinct from the older ruined one.)<ref name=Ossian>{{cite book |author=\u00c5sa Ringbom |year=2003 |title=Dolphins and mortar dating \u2013 Santa Costanza reconsidered |work=In: Songs of Ossian: Festschrift in honour of Professor Bo Ossian Lindberg |series=Taidehistoriallisia Tutkimuksia \u2013 Konsthistoriska Studier (Art Historical Studies) 27 |location=Helsinki |pp=22\u201342 |url=http://web.abo.fi/fak/hf/konstvet/stcostanza.pdf  |accessdate=1 December 2015|quote=In all this confusion we are certain of one thing: it is premature to claim that Santa Costanza was erected between 337 and 350 as a mausoleum for and by Constantina, daughter of Constantine the Great. }}</ref><ref name=roth>{{cite book |last=Roth |first=Leland M. |year=1993 |title=Understanding Architecture: Its Elements, History and Meaning |edition=First |location=Boulder, CO |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=0-06-430158-3 |p=[https://archive.org/details/understandingarc00roth/page/249 249] |url=https://archive.org/details/understandingarc00roth/page/249 }}</ref> Santa Costanza and the old Saint Agnes were both constructed over the earlier [[Catacombs of Saint Agnes|catacombs]] in which Saint Agnes is believed to be buried.\n\nAccording to the traditional view, Santa Costanza was built around the reign of [[Constantine I]] as a [[mausoleum]] for his daughter [[Constantina]], later also known as Constantia or Costanza, who died in AD 354.{{sfn|Lowden|1997|p=41}} However, more recent excavations have called this date (and therefore the original purpose of the building) into question. Ultimately, Constantina's sarcophagus was housed here, but it may have been moved from an earlier location.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kleiner |first1=Fred |title=Gardner's Art Through the Ages: A Global History |date=2015 |publisher=Wadsworth Publishing}}</ref>\n\nThe mausoleum is of circular form with an ambulatory surrounding a central dome. The fabric of Santa Costanza survives in essentially its original form. Despite the loss of the coloured stone veneers of the walls, some damage to the [[mosaic]]s and incorrect restoration, the  building stands in excellent condition as a prime example of [[Early Christian art and architecture]]. The vaults of the apses and ambulatory display well preserved examples of  Late Roman mosaics. A key component which is missing from the decorative scheme is the mosaic of the central dome. In the sixteenth-century, [[watercolour]]s were made of this central dome so the pictorial scheme can be hypothetically reconstructed.<ref name=Lowden97_43>{{harvnb|Lowden|1997|p=43}}.</ref> The large [[Porphyry (geology)|porphyry]] [[sarcophagus]] of either Constantina or her sister Helena has survived intact, and is now in the [[Vatican Museum]] - an object of great significance to the study of the art of Late Antiquity.{{r|Lowden97_43|Ossian}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Piranesi-2022.jpg|thumb|upright= 1.5|[[giovanni Battista Piranesi|Piranesi's]] 18th-century reconstruction of the original plan of the funerary hall and two mausolea, with Santa Costanza at top (modern views do not support the lower one). The ground slopes away sharply on the right, and there are large buttresses, which survive. [[Sant'Agnese fuori le mura]] would be outside the image below the bottom left corner.<ref>For an updated plan see: {{cite book |last=McClendon |first=Charles B. |year=2005 |title=The Origins of Medieval Architecture: Building in Europe, A.D. 600-900 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-030010688-6 |p=32 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P572amlqdksC&pg=PA32 }}</ref>]]\n\n===Location===\nSanta Costanza is located a minute's walk to the side of the Via Nomentana, a short way outside the ancient walls of Rome. The road follows the ancient Roman route which runs north-east from Rome to [[Nomentum]] or [[Mentana]]. The area was an Imperial family estate, and the bodies of the sisters were both brought considerable distances to be buried there: [[Ammianus]] records that Constantina's body was brought back from [[Bithynia]], and Helena's from [[Gaul]] (''History'' XIV: 11, 6).{{sfn|Webb|2001|pp=250-1}}\n\nThe mausoleum was built over the [[Catacombs of Saint Agnes|catacombs]] that contained the relics of Saint Agnes, who was martyred as a thirteen-year-old, and which was attached to the ancient basilica of Saint Agnese mid-way along the liturgical north side.<ref name=roth/> The basilica was originally a \"funerary hall\" rather than a church in the modern sense. Later legend considerably elaborated Constantina's devotion to Saint Agnes, but it now cannot be determined if this was a factor in the choice of location, although in general terms early Christians believed that their souls benefited from being buried close to martyrs, which was almost certainly a major attraction of the funerary hall to those who paid to be buried in it. Attaching an important mausoleum as an annex to a church was a common practice in Rome and can be seen the cases of other Roman churches such as the [[Mausoleum of Helena]] (Constantine's mother, not his daughter), which was attached to the basilica of [[Santi Marcellino e Pietro ad Duas Lauros]], now a ruin.{{sfn|Krautheimer|1979|p=66}} \n[[File:Constantinian Basilica - Sant'Agnese fuori le mura - Rome 2016 (2).jpg|thumb|left|upright= 1.5|View into the apse of the ruined basilica, from in front of Santa Costanza]]\nOf the original Basilica of St Agnese, only about a third of the main outer wall survives, from the north side and the apse at the eastern end, but at less than the original height. By the 7th-century the basilica had fallen into ruins and was too large to be refurbished, and the current much smaller Basilica of [[Sant'Agnese fuori le mura]] was built to replace it, a few metres away.\n\n===Purpose===\nIt was traditionally thought that construction began during the reign of [[Emperor Constantine I]] or shortly after, as an early history, the ''[[Liber Pontificalis]]'', records that [[Pope Silvester I]] (d. 335) baptized Constantina and her paternal aunt in a [[baptistry]] built by Constantine there at the same time as the funerary hall. This was assumed to be the structure that survives. But excavations in 1992 discovered an earlier building beneath, and the existing building is now dated to around 350 AD.<ref>{{harvnb|Webb|2001|p=249}}; for a superimposed plan of the two buildings see [[:File:Santakonstanza mausoleo oinplano.jpg]]</ref>\n\nThe structure of Santa Costanza reflects its original function as the mausoleum of one or both Constantine's two daughters, Constantia and Helena, rather than as the church it became much later. The centralized design put \"direct physical emphasis on the person or place to be honored\"<ref name=\"MichaelGough\">Michael Gough, ''The Origins of Christian Art'' (New York: Praeger Publishers, Inc., 1973), 58.</ref> and was popular for mausoleums and places of baptisms at this time. Other early Christian buildings with a similar origin and a circular plan include [[Split Cathedral]], built within [[Diocletian's Palace]] as his mausoleum, and the [[Arch of Galerius and Rotunda|Rotunda of Galerius]] (now the Church of St. George]] in [[Thessaloniki]] built as a mausoleum for [[Galerius]].<ref name=\"MichaelGough\" />\n\nThe huge funerary hall or Constantinian basilica gradually fell out of use and into ruins, with the base of the wall now surviving for about a third of the original circuit of exterior walls, but Santa Costanza has survived all but intact. It is documented that [[Pope Nicholas I]] celebrated mass there in 865, the first time that \"Santa Costanza\" is recorded as its name, but its consecration as a church was not until 1254, by [[Pope Alexander IV]], who had what were believed to be the remains of Constantia removed from the larger sarcophagus and placed under a central altar.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=251}}\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:S Costanza - facciata 1160930.JPG|thumb|upright= 1.25|The facade today]]\n\n===Structure===\nSanta Costanza is a circular, centralized structure, with a circular [[ambulatory]] ringing a high central space topped by a shallow dome, which is raised on a round [[Tholobate|drum]], as can be seen from the exterior. It is built of brick-faced concrete and its structure is basically two rings supported by columns placed around a vertical central axis. The upper ring sits on the columns while the \"lower ring encloses a circular ambulatory whose space flows between the columns into the axial cylinder.\"<ref>William L. MacDonald, ''Early Christian & Byzantine Architecture'' (New York: George Braziller, Inc., 1962), 22.</ref> This design essentially creates two spaces or two worlds, that of the ambulatory and that of the upper dome. The screens of the ambulatory and inner ring create a dark contrast to the bright upper space of the dome. This contrast of light can be seen in the picture of the main interior. The single door, flanked by two arched niches, would originally have been an internal arch or doorway leading straight into the Constaninian basilica or funerary hall, half-way along its length. There is a short vestibule inside the door, opening to the ambulatory. \n[[File:Wide angle view - Santa Costanza - Rome 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Interior view.]]\nAn arched arcade with twelve pairs of granite columns decorated with [[composite order|composite capitals]] supports the drum below the dome, and separates the area of the ambulatory beyond, which is much darker, as light from twelve windows in the [[clerestory]] does not reach this area as well. In contrast the central area is well-lit, creating interplay between dark and light in the interior.\n\nThe number of arches, pairs of columns and windows could be a reference to the [[Twelve Apostles]]. Opposite the entrance in this central space there is \"a kind of baldacchino...rises above a porphyry plaque which, below the middle arch of the center room, once seems to have carried the princess's sarcophagus\".{{sfn|Krautheimer|1979|p=68}} This is where the sarcophagus of Constantina, or perhaps the second one, would have rested. The ambulatory is [[barrel-vault]]ed and is 22.5 meters or 74 feet in diameter.{{r|Lowden97_43}} The ambulatory has most of the surviving mosaics in the church. Larger arches mark the cardinal points in the mausoleum. The walls were probably covered in slabs of colourful marble, as was usual in imperial buildings. Santa Costanza was also to some extent a new type of building. It was different from earlier styles in that the roof, which would previously have been typically flat and made with wood, was instead designed as a dome and vault.<ref>Walter Lowrie, ''Monuments of the Early Church'' (New York: The MacMillan Company, 1923), 139.</ref>\n\n===Decoration===\n[[File:RomaSCostanzaInterno1.jpg|thumb|The mosaics of the ambulatory vault and the paired columns]]\n\n====Mosaics====\nThe mosaics of Santa Costanza are important examples of [[Early Christian art]], and even rarer examples of secular palace ceiling mosaics. The [[apse]]s, central dome, and ambulatory all had mosaic decoration, though that in the dome no longer survives.\n\n====Mosaics in the apses====\n[[File:Santa Costanza. Mosaic del S. VII \u201cTraditio Legis\u201d adjusted.JPG|thumb|Mosaic with the ''[[Traditio Legis]]'']]\nIn the ambulatory wall there are two shallow apses, each with a mosaic showing Christ as the [[Pantocrator]], the earliest surviving examples of this depiction; they probably date to the 5th or 7th century, though there has been much discussion of this.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=251}} Like many mosaics of the period, both have suffered from restoration and both show elements of Roman imperial imagery, representing early examples of the conflation of this with Christian art. A mosaic with two women wearing white, reported as being behind the sarcophagus in the Renaissance, has now gone and was never drawn.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=251}}\n\nOne of the apses shows a ''[[traditio legis]]'': Christ is shown with Saints Peter and Paul giving Peter the scroll representing law, with the inscription, \"DOMINUS PACEM DAT,\" or \"The Lord is giving Peace.\" A few sheep represent his role as shepherd governing and leading his flock. Christ is clothed in golden robes, suggesting his power and supremacy. He is shown rising above paradise, which further shows his dominance over both heaven and earth.{{sfn|Deckers|2007|p=95}}\n\nIn the second apse, Christ appears somewhat more simply but still as supremely powerful. His robes are not quite as rich as in the other apse, but still suggest power. He wears a simple tunic but it is purple and gold. This suggests not only holy power, but human power given that purple is the color of royalty and the gold stripes suggestion a connection to the Roman emperors. Peter also approaches Christ in supplication, like one would approach the Emperor. This is one of the first examples in Christian art of Christ being portrayed in the same way as the emperor or royalty. It is a concept that would later be prevalent in Christian art and architecture. In this apse Christ is not just portrayed as royalty but as the ruler of the world, of all existence. He sits atop a blue sphere, a clear symbol for the world or universe. From this perch he hands keys to Peter. This is a clear sign of Christ, and the power of heaven, giving authority and holy power to man. It is also important to note that Peter was Rome's first bishop so this meant Roman authority was sanctioned by God. This concept and picture of Christ as the almighty ruler and creator of the world would be the norm in the artwork of later churches, but it first appears here at Santa Costanza.{{sfn|Deckers|2007|p=96}}\n\n====Mosaics in the ambulatory====\n[[File:RomaSCostanzaMosaici02.jpg|thumb|Mosaic in the ambulatory]]\nThe 4th-century mosaics on the ambulatory vault are contemporary with the building, and show a stark contrast to those in the apses, being essentially secular, with panels containing geometric patterns, small heads or figures within compartmented frames, birds with branches of foliage, vases and other objects, and vine patterns with cherubs harvesting and wine-making. This last type of scene also appears on Constantina's sarcophagus, as it does on the ends of the [[Sarcophagus of Junius Bassus]]. While the mosaics of the apses have very clear Christian imagery, those in the ambulatory are much more secular and could be considered Dionysiac with their images of grapes, fruit, birds, and mythological figures.<ref name=Beckwith70_12>{{harvnb|Beckwith|1970|p=12}}.</ref> This is especially true of the floor mosaics which were similar in style to those in the ambulatory, filled with cupids, birds, and Bacchus and grapevines. This may reflect the merging of pagan and Christian values in Rome,<ref>Marilyn Stokstad, ''Medieval Art'' (New York: Harper & Row Publishers, 1986), 29.</ref> or alternatively construction under the non-Christian Julian.{{r|Ossian}}  These mosaics probably represent the sort of decoration found in the Imperial palaces of the period, and in general have needed little restoration.\n\n====Central dome====\nThe mosaics of the central dome no longer exist, but a picture of them can still be reconstructed as between 1538 and 1540 [[Francisco de Holanda]] made watercolour copies of what then survived. In these several biblical scenes appear, resembling catacomb paintings from the 3rd century, including Susanna and the Elders, Tobias, the sacrifice of Cain and Abel, the sacrifice of Elias on Mount Carmel, possibly Lot receiving the angels, Moses striking the rock for water, and possibly even Noah building the ark. The upper row of mosaics, largely missing by the 16th century, is thought to have had scenes from the New Testament since it has the Miracle of the Centurion. These mosaics have [[caryatid]]s and acanthus-scrolls and a calendar of saints in the upper row.{{r|Beckwith70_12}} This, in conjunction with the two apses is where the majority of Christian imagery occurs.\n\n===Sarcophagi===\n[[Image:0 Sarcofago di Costantina - Museo Pio-Clementino - Vatican (1).JPG|thumb|Sarcophagus of Constantina, [[Vatican Museums]], originally stood in the mausoleum]]\nTwo large porphyry sarcophagi from the church are now in the Vatican; the larger and more famous (illustrated) in the [[Vatican Museums]], where it was moved during the late 18th century and is on display.{{r|Lowden97_43}} The smaller was moved in St Peter's itself (left transept) in 1606. It is now thought that the larger sarcophagus traditionally related to Constantina may in fact have housed her sister Helena, and the less spectacular one, also removed to the Vatican, was actually Constantina's.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=252}}\n\nConstantina's sarcophagus has complex symbolic designs in [[relief]]: \"the surface is dominated by an intricate pattern of stylized vine-stems into which are fitted cherubs...with this scene of Dionysiac exuberance, and the hope of future blessedness which it implies, two peacocks, birds of immortality, are completely in accord\".<ref name=Milburn88_77>{{harvnb|Milburn|1988|p=77}}</ref> The scene presents an image of nature and plenty complete with grape vines, sheep and birds. The putti are framed in [[acanthus (ornament)|acanthus]] scrolls, above which there are several images of masks. Aside from the natural scene, there are also four portraits including Constantia herself, \"on the lid, four graceful portrait heads, one apparently that of Constantina, look calmly out over this assurance that the best is yet to be\".{{r|Milburn88_77}} The imagery presented of wine and nature are not inherently Christian but could be perceived as such considering the use of wine in the [[Eucharist]]. Or they could be perceived as a connection to [[Dionysus|Bacchus]], the God of Wine.{{r|Lowden97_43}} This style of sarcophagus would cease to be used in Rome by the end of the fourth century, and this sarcophagus of Constantia is a prime example of the style.{{r|Milburn88_77}}\n\nThe sarcophagus is massive with the chest measuring 128&nbsp;cm or 4&nbsp;ft 2{{frac|3|8}} in high, 233&nbsp;cm or 7&nbsp;ft 7{{frac|1|2}} in long, and 157&nbsp;cm or 5&nbsp;ft 1{{frac|3|4}} in wide.{{r|Lowden97_43}} It is made of [[Porphyry (geology)|porphyry]], a hard purple stone, reserved by the Romans for use only by the imperial family, whose colour purple was. It was quarried from only one place, Mons Porphyriticus (Coptos, Egypt), making it even more exclusive.{{r|Beckwith70_12}} It appears, but can not be certain, that the sarcophagus of Constantina is a copy of that of Constantine I, her father, which is now lost. A piece of what is believed to be his sarcophagus is similar in style and of the same material.{{sfn|Beckwith|1970|p=13}} A cast replica has been placed in the church, though in the ambulatory; presumably its original position was in the centre of the church, now occupied by the altar.  There is another in the [[Museum of Roman Civilization]] in the city.\n\n==Alternative views==\nSome consider that the building was only later reassigned as a church dedicated to Santa Costanza.{{sfn|Deckers|2007|pp=95-6}}  The veneration of Constantina as \"Santa Costanza\" (Saint Constance) is only known from the 16th century onward, and her name is not included in the [[Roman Martyrology]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Sch\u00e4fer |first=Joachim |year=2003 |title=\u00d6kumenisches Heiligenlexikon - Konstantia |format=CD-ROM |isbn=3-00-012997-9 |language=de |url=https://www.heiligenlexikon.de/BiographienK/Konstantia.htm }}</ref> An original structure might be located underneath the current church, as a possibly [[Tetraconch|triconch]]-shaped structure was partially excavated in 1987 and 1992 and computer-reconstructed by David J. Stanley.{{r|Ossian}}\n\nThat could suggest that the current church is the second Christian building on the site, and may be some decades later than traditionally thought, being built as a mausoleum for Constantina's sister Helena in the reign of her husband [[Julian the Apostate]]. (This would be odd, however, because Julian was a staunch pagan.) If true, the larger of the two porphyry sarcophagi there would belong to Helena, and the smaller to Constantina, the opposite of what has been traditionally thought. The earlier triconch building of the 330s was probably indeed built for Constantina, but she later had to take second place to her sister. Then, as Constantina's fame as a saintly figure developed in the Middle Ages, their roles became reversed in the popular mind.{{r|Ossian}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Architecture of ancient Rome]]\n*[[Early Christian sarcophagi]]\n*[[Early Christian art and architecture]]\n*[[History of Roman and Byzantine domes]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Beckwith |first=John |year=1970 |title=Early Christian and Byzantine Art |location=Baltimore |publisher=Penguin Books |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Deckers |first=Johannes G. |year=2007 |title=Constantine the Great and Early Christian Art |location=New Haven |publisher=Yale University Press |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Krautheimer |first=Richard |year=1979 |title=Early Christian and Byzantine Architecture |publisher=Penguin Books |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Lowden |first=John |year=1997 |title=Early Christian and Byzantine Art |publisher=Phaidon Press |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Milburn |first=Robert |year=1988 |title=Early Christian Art and Architecture |publisher=Scolar Press |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Webb |first=Matilda |year=2001 |title=The churches and catacombs of early Christian Rome: a comprehensive guide |publisher=Sussex Academic Press |isbn=978-190221058-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_churches_and_catacombs_of_early_Chri.html?id=Y-ROAAAAMAAJ |ref=harv }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Blasen, Philippe Henri, \"De sancta Agnete Romana e fontibus Latinis antiquissimis... Sainte Agn\u00e8s de Rome dans les sources latines les plus anciennes jusqu'\u00e0 Augustin d'Hippone\", ''Acta Musei Napocensis'' 45-46 (2011): 253-281.\n* Stanley, David J., \"New Discoveries at Santa Costanza\", ''Dumbarton Oaks Papers'' 48 (1994): 257-261.\n*[[Kurt Weitzmann|Weitzmann, Kurt]], ed., ''[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15324coll10/id/156533 Age of spirituality: late antique and early Christian art, third to seventh century]'', no. 108 & 246, 1979, [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York, {{ISBN|9780870991790}}; full text available online from The Metropolitan Museum of Art Libraries\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons-inline}}\n* [http://www.roman-emperors.org/constan.htm Constantina] - De Imperatoribus Romanis\n* [http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/italy/rome/costanza/costanza.html Santa Costanza] - Santa Costanza Photo Gallery\n*High-resolution 360\u00b0 Panoramas and Images of [https://mcid.mcah.columbia.edu/art-atlas/ancient-and-early-christian-sites-rome/santa-constanza Santa Costanza | Art Atlas]\n\n{{Coord|41.922614|N|12.517375|E|dim:20_region:IT-RM_type:landmark|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:4th-century churches]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Rome|Costanza]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Rome]]\n[[Category:Early Christian art]]\n[[Category:Palaeo-Christian architecture in Italy]]\n[[Category:Rome Q. XVII Trieste]]\n[[Category:Round churches]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Santa Costanza - vista dalla basilica costantiniana.jpg|thumb|upright= 1.5|View of the mausoleum of Santa Costanza and the remaining wall of the Constantinian basilica (photo taken from its apse).]] \n[[File:Piranesi-2023.jpg|thumb|upright= 1.5|[[giovanni Battista Piranesi|Piranesi's]] etching of the elevations of the site]]\n'''Santa Costanza''' is a 4th-century church in [[Rome]], Italy, on the [[Via Nomentana]], which runs north-east out of the city. It is a round building with well preserved original layout and mosaics. It has been built adjacent to a horseshoe-shaped church, now in ruins, which has been identified as the initial 4th-century cemeterial [[basilica]] of [[Saint Agnes]]. (Note that the much later [[Sant'Agnese fuori le mura|Church of St Agnes]], still standing nearby, is distinct from the older ruined one.)<ref name=Ossian>{{cite book |author=\u00c5sa Ringbom |year=2003 |title=Dolphins and mortar dating \u2013 Santa Costanza reconsidered |work=In: Songs of Ossian: Festschrift in honour of Professor Bo Ossian Lindberg |series=Taidehistoriallisia Tutkimuksia \u2013 Konsthistoriska Studier (Art Historical Studies) 27 |location=Helsinki |pp=22\u201342 |url=http://web.abo.fi/fak/hf/konstvet/stcostanza.pdf  |accessdate=1 December 2015|quote=In all this confusion we are certain of one thing: it is premature to claim that Santa Costanza was erected between 337 and 350 as a mausoleum for and by Constantina, daughter of Constantine the Great. }}</ref><ref name=roth>{{cite book |last=Roth |first=Leland M. |year=1993 |title=Understanding Architecture: Its Elements, History and Meaning |edition=First |location=Boulder, CO |publisher=Westview Press |isbn=0-06-430158-3 |p=[https://archive.org/details/understandingarc00roth/page/249 249] |url=https://archive.org/details/understandingarc00roth/page/249 }}</ref> Santa Costanza and the old Saint Agnes were both constructed over the earlier [[Catacombs of Saint Agnes|catacombs]] in which Saint Agnes is believed to be buried.\n\nAccording to the traditional view, Santa Costanza was built around the reign of [[Constantine I]] as a [[mausoleum]] for his daughter [[Constantina]], later also known as Constantia or Costanza, who died in AD 354.{{sfn|Lowden|1997|p=41}} However, more recent excavations have called this date (and therefore the original purpose of the building) into question. Ultimately, Constantina's sarcophagus was housed here, but it may have been moved from an earlier location.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kleiner |first1=Fred |title=Gardner's Art Though the Ages: A Global History |date=2015 |publisher=Wadsworth Publishing}}</ref>\n\nThe mausoleum is of circular form with an ambulatory surrounding a central dome. The fabric of Santa Costanza survives in essentially its original form. Despite the loss of the coloured stone veneers of the walls, some damage to the [[mosaic]]s and incorrect restoration, the  building stands in excellent condition as a prime example of [[Early Christian art and architecture]]. The vaults of the apses and ambulatory display well preserved examples of  Late Roman mosaics. A key component which is missing from the decorative scheme is the mosaic of the central dome. In the sixteenth-century, [[watercolour]]s were made of this central dome so the pictorial scheme can be hypothetically reconstructed.<ref name=Lowden97_43>{{harvnb|Lowden|1997|p=43}}.</ref> The large [[Porphyry (geology)|porphyry]] [[sarcophagus]] of either Constantina or her sister Helena has survived intact, and is now in the [[Vatican Museum]] - an object of great significance to the study of the art of Late Antiquity.{{r|Lowden97_43|Ossian}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:Piranesi-2022.jpg|thumb|upright= 1.5|[[giovanni Battista Piranesi|Piranesi's]] 18th-century reconstruction of the original plan of the funerary hall and two mausolea, with Santa Costanza at top (modern views do not support the lower one). The ground slopes away sharply on the right, and there are large buttresses, which survive. [[Sant'Agnese fuori le mura]] would be outside the image below the bottom left corner.<ref>For an updated plan see: {{cite book |last=McClendon |first=Charles B. |year=2005 |title=The Origins of Medieval Architecture: Building in Europe, A.D. 600-900 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-030010688-6 |p=32 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P572amlqdksC&pg=PA32 }}</ref>]]\n\n===Location===\nSanta Costanza is located a minute's walk to the side of the Via Nomentana, a short way outside the ancient walls of Rome. The road follows the ancient Roman route which runs north-east from Rome to [[Nomentum]] or [[Mentana]]. The area was an Imperial family estate, and the bodies of the sisters were both brought considerable distances to be buried there: [[Ammianus]] records that Constantina's body was brought back from [[Bithynia]], and Helena's from [[Gaul]] (''History'' XIV: 11, 6).{{sfn|Webb|2001|pp=250-1}}\n\nThe mausoleum was built over the [[Catacombs of Saint Agnes|catacombs]] that contained the relics of Saint Agnes, who was martyred as a thirteen-year-old, and which was attached to the ancient basilica of Saint Agnese mid-way along the liturgical north side.<ref name=roth/> The basilica was originally a \"funerary hall\" rather than a church in the modern sense. Later legend considerably elaborated Constantina's devotion to Saint Agnes, but it now cannot be determined if this was a factor in the choice of location, although in general terms early Christians believed that their souls benefited from being buried close to martyrs, which was almost certainly a major attraction of the funerary hall to those who paid to be buried in it. Attaching an important mausoleum as an annex to a church was a common practice in Rome and can be seen the cases of other Roman churches such as the [[Mausoleum of Helena]] (Constantine's mother, not his daughter), which was attached to the basilica of [[Santi Marcellino e Pietro ad Duas Lauros]], now a ruin.{{sfn|Krautheimer|1979|p=66}} \n[[File:Constantinian Basilica - Sant'Agnese fuori le mura - Rome 2016 (2).jpg|thumb|left|upright= 1.5|View into the apse of the ruined basilica, from in front of Santa Costanza]]\nOf the original Basilica of St Agnese, only about a third of the main outer wall survives, from the north side and the apse at the eastern end, but at less than the original height. By the 7th-century the basilica had fallen into ruins and was too large to be refurbished, and the current much smaller Basilica of [[Sant'Agnese fuori le mura]] was built to replace it, a few metres away.\n\n===Purpose===\nIt was traditionally thought that construction began during the reign of [[Emperor Constantine I]] or shortly after, as an early history, the ''[[Liber Pontificalis]]'', records that [[Pope Silvester I]] (d. 335) baptized Constantina and her paternal aunt in a [[baptistry]] built by Constantine there at the same time as the funerary hall. This was assumed to be the structure that survives. But excavations in 1992 discovered an earlier building beneath, and the existing building is now dated to around 350 AD.<ref>{{harvnb|Webb|2001|p=249}}; for a superimposed plan of the two buildings see [[:File:Santakonstanza mausoleo oinplano.jpg]]</ref>\n\nThe structure of Santa Costanza reflects its original function as the mausoleum of one or both Constantine's two daughters, Constantia and Helena, rather than as the church it became much later. The centralized design put \"direct physical emphasis on the person or place to be honored\"<ref name=\"MichaelGough\">Michael Gough, ''The Origins of Christian Art'' (New York: Praeger Publishers, Inc., 1973), 58.</ref> and was popular for mausoleums and places of baptisms at this time. Other early Christian buildings with a similar origin and a circular plan include [[Split Cathedral]], built within [[Diocletian's Palace]] as his mausoleum, and the [[Arch of Galerius and Rotunda|Rotunda of Galerius]] (now the Church of St. George]] in [[Thessaloniki]] built as a mausoleum for [[Galerius]].<ref name=\"MichaelGough\" />\n\nThe huge funerary hall or Constantinian basilica gradually fell out of use and into ruins, with the base of the wall now surviving for about a third of the original circuit of exterior walls, but Santa Costanza has survived all but intact. It is documented that [[Pope Nicholas I]] celebrated mass there in 865, the first time that \"Santa Costanza\" is recorded as its name, but its consecration as a church was not until 1254, by [[Pope Alexander IV]], who had what were believed to be the remains of Constantia removed from the larger sarcophagus and placed under a central altar.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=251}}\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:S Costanza - facciata 1160930.JPG|thumb|upright= 1.25|The facade today]]\n\n===Structure===\nSanta Costanza is a circular, centralized structure, with a circular [[ambulatory]] ringing a high central space topped by a shallow dome, which is raised on a round [[Tholobate|drum]], as can be seen from the exterior. It is built of brick-faced concrete and its structure is basically two rings supported by columns placed around a vertical central axis. The upper ring sits on the columns while the \"lower ring encloses a circular ambulatory whose space flows between the columns into the axial cylinder.\"<ref>William L. MacDonald, ''Early Christian & Byzantine Architecture'' (New York: George Braziller, Inc., 1962), 22.</ref> This design essentially creates two spaces or two worlds, that of the ambulatory and that of the upper dome. The screens of the ambulatory and inner ring create a dark contrast to the bright upper space of the dome. This contrast of light can be seen in the picture of the main interior. The single door, flanked by two arched niches, would originally have been an internal arch or doorway leading straight into the Constaninian basilica or funerary hall, half-way along its length. There is a short vestibule inside the door, opening to the ambulatory. \n[[File:Wide angle view - Santa Costanza - Rome 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Interior view.]]\nAn arched arcade with twelve pairs of granite columns decorated with [[composite order|composite capitals]] supports the drum below the dome, and separates the area of the ambulatory beyond, which is much darker, as light from twelve windows in the [[clerestory]] does not reach this area as well. In contrast the central area is well-lit, creating interplay between dark and light in the interior.\n\nThe number of arches, pairs of columns and windows could be a reference to the [[Twelve Apostles]]. Opposite the entrance in this central space there is \"a kind of baldacchino...rises above a porphyry plaque which, below the middle arch of the center room, once seems to have carried the princess's sarcophagus\".{{sfn|Krautheimer|1979|p=68}} This is where the sarcophagus of Constantina, or perhaps the second one, would have rested. The ambulatory is [[barrel-vault]]ed and is 22.5 meters or 74 feet in diameter.{{r|Lowden97_43}} The ambulatory has most of the surviving mosaics in the church. Larger arches mark the cardinal points in the mausoleum. The walls were probably covered in slabs of colourful marble, as was usual in imperial buildings. Santa Costanza was also to some extent a new type of building. It was different from earlier styles in that the roof, which would previously have been typically flat and made with wood, was instead designed as a dome and vault.<ref>Walter Lowrie, ''Monuments of the Early Church'' (New York: The MacMillan Company, 1923), 139.</ref>\n\n===Decoration===\n[[File:RomaSCostanzaInterno1.jpg|thumb|The mosaics of the ambulatory vault and the paired columns]]\n\n====Mosaics====\nThe mosaics of Santa Costanza are important examples of [[Early Christian art]], and even rarer examples of secular palace ceiling mosaics. The [[apse]]s, central dome, and ambulatory all had mosaic decoration, though that in the dome no longer survives.\n\n====Mosaics in the apses====\n[[File:Santa Costanza. Mosaic del S. VII \u201cTraditio Legis\u201d adjusted.JPG|thumb|Mosaic with the ''[[Traditio Legis]]'']]\nIn the ambulatory wall there are two shallow apses, each with a mosaic showing Christ as the [[Pantocrator]], the earliest surviving examples of this depiction; they probably date to the 5th or 7th century, though there has been much discussion of this.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=251}} Like many mosaics of the period, both have suffered from restoration and both show elements of Roman imperial imagery, representing early examples of the conflation of this with Christian art. A mosaic with two women wearing white, reported as being behind the sarcophagus in the Renaissance, has now gone and was never drawn.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=251}}\n\nOne of the apses shows a ''[[traditio legis]]'': Christ is shown with Saints Peter and Paul giving Peter the scroll representing law, with the inscription, \"DOMINUS PACEM DAT,\" or \"The Lord is giving Peace.\" A few sheep represent his role as shepherd governing and leading his flock. Christ is clothed in golden robes, suggesting his power and supremacy. He is shown rising above paradise, which further shows his dominance over both heaven and earth.{{sfn|Deckers|2007|p=95}}\n\nIn the second apse, Christ appears somewhat more simply but still as supremely powerful. His robes are not quite as rich as in the other apse, but still suggest power. He wears a simple tunic but it is purple and gold. This suggests not only holy power, but human power given that purple is the color of royalty and the gold stripes suggestion a connection to the Roman emperors. Peter also approaches Christ in supplication, like one would approach the Emperor. This is one of the first examples in Christian art of Christ being portrayed in the same way as the emperor or royalty. It is a concept that would later be prevalent in Christian art and architecture. In this apse Christ is not just portrayed as royalty but as the ruler of the world, of all existence. He sits atop a blue sphere, a clear symbol for the world or universe. From this perch he hands keys to Peter. This is a clear sign of Christ, and the power of heaven, giving authority and holy power to man. It is also important to note that Peter was Rome's first bishop so this meant Roman authority was sanctioned by God. This concept and picture of Christ as the almighty ruler and creator of the world would be the norm in the artwork of later churches, but it first appears here at Santa Costanza.{{sfn|Deckers|2007|p=96}}\n\n====Mosaics in the ambulatory====\n[[File:RomaSCostanzaMosaici02.jpg|thumb|Mosaic in the ambulatory]]\nThe 4th-century mosaics on the ambulatory vault are contemporary with the building, and show a stark contrast to those in the apses, being essentially secular, with panels containing geometric patterns, small heads or figures within compartmented frames, birds with branches of foliage, vases and other objects, and vine patterns with cherubs harvesting and wine-making. This last type of scene also appears on Constantina's sarcophagus, as it does on the ends of the [[Sarcophagus of Junius Bassus]]. While the mosaics of the apses have very clear Christian imagery, those in the ambulatory are much more secular and could be considered Dionysiac with their images of grapes, fruit, birds, and mythological figures.<ref name=Beckwith70_12>{{harvnb|Beckwith|1970|p=12}}.</ref> This is especially true of the floor mosaics which were similar in style to those in the ambulatory, filled with cupids, birds, and Bacchus and grapevines. This may reflect the merging of pagan and Christian values in Rome,<ref>Marilyn Stokstad, ''Medieval Art'' (New York: Harper & Row Publishers, 1986), 29.</ref> or alternatively construction under the non-Christian Julian.{{r|Ossian}}  These mosaics probably represent the sort of decoration found in the Imperial palaces of the period, and in general have needed little restoration.\n\n====Central dome====\nThe mosaics of the central dome no longer exist, but a picture of them can still be reconstructed as between 1538 and 1540 [[Francisco de Holanda]] made watercolour copies of what then survived. In these several biblical scenes appear, resembling catacomb paintings from the 3rd century, including Susanna and the Elders, Tobias, the sacrifice of Cain and Abel, the sacrifice of Elias on Mount Carmel, possibly Lot receiving the angels, Moses striking the rock for water, and possibly even Noah building the ark. The upper row of mosaics, largely missing by the 16th century, is thought to have had scenes from the New Testament since it has the Miracle of the Centurion. These mosaics have [[caryatid]]s and acanthus-scrolls and a calendar of saints in the upper row.{{r|Beckwith70_12}} This, in conjunction with the two apses is where the majority of Christian imagery occurs.\n\n===Sarcophagi===\n[[Image:0 Sarcofago di Costantina - Museo Pio-Clementino - Vatican (1).JPG|thumb|Sarcophagus of Constantina, [[Vatican Museums]], originally stood in the mausoleum]]\nTwo large porphyry sarcophagi from the church are now in the Vatican; the larger and more famous (illustrated) in the [[Vatican Museums]], where it was moved during the late 18th century and is on display.{{r|Lowden97_43}} The smaller was moved in St Peter's itself (left transept) in 1606. It is now thought that the larger sarcophagus traditionally related to Constantina may in fact have housed her sister Helena, and the less spectacular one, also removed to the Vatican, was actually Constantina's.{{sfn|Webb|2001|p=252}}\n\nConstantina's sarcophagus has complex symbolic designs in [[relief]]: \"the surface is dominated by an intricate pattern of stylized vine-stems into which are fitted cherubs...with this scene of Dionysiac exuberance, and the hope of future blessedness which it implies, two peacocks, birds of immortality, are completely in accord\".<ref name=Milburn88_77>{{harvnb|Milburn|1988|p=77}}</ref> The scene presents an image of nature and plenty complete with grape vines, sheep and birds. The putti are framed in [[acanthus (ornament)|acanthus]] scrolls, above which there are several images of masks. Aside from the natural scene, there are also four portraits including Constantia herself, \"on the lid, four graceful portrait heads, one apparently that of Constantina, look calmly out over this assurance that the best is yet to be\".{{r|Milburn88_77}} The imagery presented of wine and nature are not inherently Christian but could be perceived as such considering the use of wine in the [[Eucharist]]. Or they could be perceived as a connection to [[Dionysus|Bacchus]], the God of Wine.{{r|Lowden97_43}} This style of sarcophagus would cease to be used in Rome by the end of the fourth century, and this sarcophagus of Constantia is a prime example of the style.{{r|Milburn88_77}}\n\nThe sarcophagus is massive with the chest measuring 128&nbsp;cm or 4&nbsp;ft 2{{frac|3|8}} in high, 233&nbsp;cm or 7&nbsp;ft 7{{frac|1|2}} in long, and 157&nbsp;cm or 5&nbsp;ft 1{{frac|3|4}} in wide.{{r|Lowden97_43}} It is made of [[Porphyry (geology)|porphyry]], a hard purple stone, reserved by the Romans for use only by the imperial family, whose colour purple was. It was quarried from only one place, Mons Porphyriticus (Coptos, Egypt), making it even more exclusive.{{r|Beckwith70_12}} It appears, but can not be certain, that the sarcophagus of Constantina is a copy of that of Constantine I, her father, which is now lost. A piece of what is believed to be his sarcophagus is similar in style and of the same material.{{sfn|Beckwith|1970|p=13}} A cast replica has been placed in the church, though in the ambulatory; presumably its original position was in the centre of the church, now occupied by the altar.  There is another in the [[Museum of Roman Civilization]] in the city.\n\n==Alternative views==\nSome consider that the building was only later reassigned as a church dedicated to Santa Costanza.{{sfn|Deckers|2007|pp=95-6}}  The veneration of Constantina as \"Santa Costanza\" (Saint Constance) is only known from the 16th century onward, and her name is not included in the [[Roman Martyrology]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Sch\u00e4fer |first=Joachim |year=2003 |title=\u00d6kumenisches Heiligenlexikon - Konstantia |format=CD-ROM |isbn=3-00-012997-9 |language=de |url=https://www.heiligenlexikon.de/BiographienK/Konstantia.htm }}</ref> An original structure might be located underneath the current church, as a possibly [[Tetraconch|triconch]]-shaped structure was partially excavated in 1987 and 1992 and computer-reconstructed by David J. Stanley.{{r|Ossian}}\n\nThat could suggest that the current church is the second Christian building on the site, and may be some decades later than traditionally thought, being built as a mausoleum for Constantina's sister Helena in the reign of her husband [[Julian the Apostate]]. (This would be odd, however, because Julian was a staunch pagan.) If true, the larger of the two porphyry sarcophagi there would belong to Helena, and the smaller to Constantina, the opposite of what has been traditionally thought. The earlier triconch building of the 330s was probably indeed built for Constantina, but she later had to take second place to her sister. Then, as Constantina's fame as a saintly figure developed in the Middle Ages, their roles became reversed in the popular mind.{{r|Ossian}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Architecture of ancient Rome]]\n*[[Early Christian sarcophagi]]\n*[[Early Christian art and architecture]]\n*[[History of Roman and Byzantine domes]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Beckwith |first=John |year=1970 |title=Early Christian and Byzantine Art |location=Baltimore |publisher=Penguin Books |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Deckers |first=Johannes G. |year=2007 |title=Constantine the Great and Early Christian Art |location=New Haven |publisher=Yale University Press |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Krautheimer |first=Richard |year=1979 |title=Early Christian and Byzantine Architecture |publisher=Penguin Books |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Lowden |first=John |year=1997 |title=Early Christian and Byzantine Art |publisher=Phaidon Press |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Milburn |first=Robert |year=1988 |title=Early Christian Art and Architecture |publisher=Scolar Press |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Webb |first=Matilda |year=2001 |title=The churches and catacombs of early Christian Rome: a comprehensive guide |publisher=Sussex Academic Press |isbn=978-190221058-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_churches_and_catacombs_of_early_Chri.html?id=Y-ROAAAAMAAJ |ref=harv }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Blasen, Philippe Henri, \"De sancta Agnete Romana e fontibus Latinis antiquissimis... Sainte Agn\u00e8s de Rome dans les sources latines les plus anciennes jusqu'\u00e0 Augustin d'Hippone\", ''Acta Musei Napocensis'' 45-46 (2011): 253-281.\n* Stanley, David J., \"New Discoveries at Santa Costanza\", ''Dumbarton Oaks Papers'' 48 (1994): 257-261.\n*[[Kurt Weitzmann|Weitzmann, Kurt]], ed., ''[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15324coll10/id/156533 Age of spirituality: late antique and early Christian art, third to seventh century]'', no. 108 & 246, 1979, [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York, {{ISBN|9780870991790}}; full text available online from The Metropolitan Museum of Art Libraries\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons-inline}}\n* [http://www.roman-emperors.org/constan.htm Constantina] - De Imperatoribus Romanis\n* [http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/italy/rome/costanza/costanza.html Santa Costanza] - Santa Costanza Photo Gallery\n*High-resolution 360\u00b0 Panoramas and Images of [https://mcid.mcah.columbia.edu/art-atlas/ancient-and-early-christian-sites-rome/santa-constanza Santa Costanza | Art Atlas]\n\n{{Coord|41.922614|N|12.517375|E|dim:20_region:IT-RM_type:landmark|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:4th-century churches]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Rome|Costanza]]\n[[Category:Mausoleums in Rome]]\n[[Category:Early Christian art]]\n[[Category:Palaeo-Christian architecture in Italy]]\n[[Category:Rome Q. XVII Trieste]]\n[[Category:Round churches]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Santa_Costanza"}
{"title_page": "Abutilon grandifolium", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Starr_070215-4594_Abutilon_grandifolium.jpg\n|genus = Abutilon\n|species = grandifolium\n|authority = ([[Carl Ludwig Willdenow|Willd.]]) [[Robert Sweet (botanist)|Sweet]]<ref name=efloras/>\n}}\n\n'''''Abutilon grandifolium''''', the '''hairy Indian mallow''', is a large shrub that is up to {{convert|3|m|abbr=on|1}} high with broad, {{convert|3|-|18|cm|abbr=on|1}} leaf blades. Flowers are axillary, with a yellow corolla {{convert|2|-|3.5|cm|abbr=on|1}} across, composed of petals {{convert|1|-|1.5|cm|abbr=on|1}} long. The fruits are ovoid-globular [[schizocarp]]s that are {{convert|1|-|1.5|cm|abbr=on|1}} in diameter and composed of ten shortly beaked mericarps, containing 2-3 seeds each.<ref name=efloras>{{eFloras|5|242412002|Abutilon grandifolium|accessdate= 15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n''A. grandifolium'' can be distinguished from [[Abutilon theophrasti|''A. theophrasti'']] by long, simple hairs on the stem rather than [[Trichomes|stellate]] hairs.\n\n==Distribution==\nThe species is native to tropical [[America]]<ref name=efloras/> and Central and South [[Africa]],<ref name=hortus>Bailey, L.H. and E.Z. Bailey, [http://www.worldcat.org/title/hortus-third-a-concise-dictionary-of-plants-cultivated-in-the-united-states-and-canada/oclc/756410167 ''Hortus Third: A Concise Dictionary of Plants Cultivated in the United States and Canada''], MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc., New York , (1977).</ref> but it is naturalised in other parts of the world, including the [[Canary Islands]], [[Hawaii]] and in [[shrubland]] and [[loam]]y areas of [[Australia]]. In Western Australia it is found in the [[Swan Coastal Plain]].<ref name=florabase>{{cite web|url= http://florabase.calm.wa.gov.au/browse/profile/19708|title=''Abutilon grandifolium'' (Willd.) Sweet|publisher=[[FloraBase]]|accessdate= March 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Threat level==\nIn Western Australia it is considered not threatened.<ref name=florabase/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.hear.org/species/abutilon_grandifolium/ ''Abutilon&nbsp;grandifolium'' information] from the [http://www.hear.org/ Hawaiian Ecosystems at Risk project (HEAR)]\n*[http://www.floradecanarias.com/abutilon_grandifolium.html ''Abutilon&nbsp;grandifolium'' in the Canary Islands]\n*[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279846080_Abutilon_grandifolium ''Abutilon grandiflorum''] in ''Flowering Plants of Africa'' 64: 76\u201383 (2015).\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q280892}}\n\n[[Category:Abutilon|grandifolium]]\n\n\n{{Malveae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Starr_070215-4594_Abutilon_grandifolium.jpg\n|genus = Abutilon\n|species = grandifolium\n|authority = ([[Carl Ludwig Willdenow|Willd.]]) [[Robert Sweet (botanist)|Sweet]]<ref name=efloras/>\n}}\n\n'''''Abutilon grandifolium''''', the '''hairy Indian mallow''', is a large shrub that is up to {{convert|3|m|abbr=on|1}} high with broad, {{convert|3|-|18|cm|abbr=on|1}} leaf blades. Flowers are axillary, with a yellow corolla {{convert|2|-|3.5|cm|abbr=on|1}} across, composed of petals {{convert|1|-|1.5|cm|abbr=on|1}} long. The fruits are ovoid-globular [[schizocarp]]s that are {{convert|1|-|1.5|cm|abbr=on|1}} in diameter and composed of ten shortly beaked mericarps, containing 2-3 seeds each.<ref name=efloras>{{eFloras|5|242412002|Abutilon grandifolium|accessdate= 15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n''A. grandifolium'' can be distinguished from [[Abutilon theophrasti|''A. theophrasti'']] by long, simple hairs on the stem rather than [[Trichomes|stellate]] hairs.\n\n==Distribution==\nThe species is native to tropical [[America]]<ref name=efloras/> and Central and South [[Africa]],<ref name=hortus>Bailey, L.H. and E.Z. Bailey, [http://www.worldcat.org/title/hortus-third-a-concise-dictionary-of-plants-cultivated-in-the-united-states-and-canada/oclc/756410167 ''Hortus Third: A Concise Dictionary of Plants Cultivated in the United States and Canada''], MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc., New York , (1977).</ref> but it is naturalised in other parts of the world, including the [[Canary Islands]], [[Hawaii]] and in [[shrubland]] and [[loam]]y areas of [[Australia]]. In Western Australia it was found in the [[Swan Coastal Plain]].<ref name=florabase>{{cite web|url= http://florabase.calm.wa.gov.au/browse/profile/19708|title=''Abutilon grandifolium'' (Willd.) Sweet|publisher=[[FloraBase]]|accessdate= March 10, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Threat level==\nIn Western Australia it is considered not threatened.<ref name=florabase/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.hear.org/species/abutilon_grandifolium/ ''Abutilon&nbsp;grandifolium'' information] from the [http://www.hear.org/ Hawaiian Ecosystems at Risk project (HEAR)]\n*[http://www.floradecanarias.com/abutilon_grandifolium.html ''Abutilon&nbsp;grandifolium'' in the Canary Islands]\n*[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/279846080_Abutilon_grandifolium ''Abutilon grandiflorum''] in ''Flowering Plants of Africa'' 64: 76\u201383 (2015).\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q280892}}\n\n[[Category:Abutilon|grandifolium]]\n\n\n{{Malveae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dr. Van Nostrand", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution:present tense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abutilon_grandifolium"}
{"title_page": "Bandung", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bandung\n| official_name                   = City of Bandung<br>{{nobold|''Kota Bandung''}}\n| settlement_type      = [[List of regencies and cities of Indonesia|City]]\n| translit_lang1       = Other\n| translit_lang1_type1 = [[Sundanese alphabet|Sundanese]]\n| translit_lang1_info1 = {{Sund|\u1b8a\u1ba7\u1b92 \u1b98\u1b94\u1baa\u1b93\u1ba5\u1b80}}\n| image_skyline                = Montage of Bandung.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise, from top: [[Gedung Sate]], [[Grand Mosque of Bandung]], Bandung at night, [[Pasupati Bridge]], [[Merdeka Building]]\n| image_flag                      = Municipal Flag of Bandung, Indonesia.svg\n| image_shield                    = Lambang Kota Bandung.svg\n| nicknames                       = ''Kota Kembang'' (City of Flowers)<br/>''Parijs van Java'' ([[Dutch language|Dutch]]) (Paris of Java)\n| motto                           = Clean, Prosperous, Devout, Friendly\n| image_map                       = Map of West Java highlighting Bandung City.svg\n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = Location within [[West Java]]\n| pushpin_map                     = Indonesia_Java#Indonesia\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in [[Java]] and [[Indonesia]]\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|6.9120|S|107.6097|E|region:ID-JB_type:city|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint                   = \n| coordinates_footnotes           = \n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{nowrap|{{flag|Indonesia|size=23px}}}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces of Indonesia|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|West Java}}\n| established_title               = Founded\n| established_date                = 25 September 1810<ref name=\"aniversary\">http://disdik.jabarprov.go.id/news/461/asal-muasal-dan-sejarah-bandung</ref>\n| established_title1              = [[City status in Indonesia|Incorporated]]<br>{{nobold|(as ''gemeente'')}}\n| established_date1               = 1 April 1906<ref name=\"aniversary\"/>\n| parts_type                      = Administrative division\n| parts                           = 30 [[List of districts of West Java|districts]]<br>153 [[Villages of Indonesia|urban villages]]\n| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = Bandung City Government\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = [[Oded Muhammad Danial]]\n| leader_title1                   = Vice Mayor\n| leader_name1                    = \n| total_type                      = Total\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = 167.67\n| area_land_km2                   = \n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_metro_km2                  = 1876.8\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 768\n| elevation_ft                    = 2520\n| population_urban                = 2,575,478 \n| population_metro                = 8,201,928 ([[Bandung Metropolitan Area|3rd]])\n| population_as_of                = 2015\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 = 3rd\n| population_demonyms             = Bandungite<br/>Warga Bandung <small>([[Indonesian language|id]])</small><br/>Urang Bandung <small>([[Sundanese language|su]])</small>\n| demographics_type1              = Demographics\n| demographics1_title1            = {{nowrap|Ethnic groups}}\n| timezone1                       = [[Time in Indonesia|Indonesia Western Time]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +7\n| timezone1_DST                   = \n| utc_offset1_DST                 = \n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in Indonesia|Postcodes]]\n| postal_code                     = 401xx, 402xx, 406xx\n| area_code                       = (+62) 22\n| area_code_type                  = [[Telephone numbers in Indonesia|Area code]]\n| registration_plate              = D\n| blank_name_sec1                 = [[Human Development Index|HDI]]\n| blank_info_sec1                 = {{increase}} 0.801 ({{fontcolor|#007B00|very high}})\n| blank_name_sec2                 = Largest [[Districts of Indonesia|district]] by area\n| blank_info_sec2                 = Gedebage \u2013 {{convert|9.58|km2|sqmi}}\n| blank1_name_sec2                = Largest district by population\n| blank1_info_sec2                = Babakan Ciparay (147,388 \u2013 2015 est)\n| website                         = {{URL|portal.bandung.go.id|Official Portal}}\n| size                            = \n| caption                         = Bandung Tengah CBD\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Sundanese people|Sundanese]]<br/> [[Sundanese people|Javanese]]<br/> [[Chinese Indonesian|Chinese]]<br> [[Arab Indonesian|Arab]]<br>[[Indian Indonesian|Indian]]\n| demographics1_title2            = Religion<ref name=\"SP2010agama\">Data Sensus Penduduk 2010 - Badan Pusat Statistik Republik Indonesia <http://sp2010.bps.go.id/index.php/site/tabel?tid=321&wid=3200000000&lang=id></ref>\n| demographics1_info2             =[[Islam]] 91.70%<br> [[Protestantism]] 5.36%<br> [[Catholicism]] 1.95%<br> [[Buddhism]] 0.49%<br> [[Hinduism]] 0.09%<br> [[Confucianism]] 0.03%\nOthers 0.02%\n| pushpin_label                   = \n| registration_plate_type         = [[Vehicle registration plates of Indonesia|Registration plate]]\n}}\n\n'''Bandung''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0|n|d|\u028a|\u014b}}) is the capital of [[West Java]] province in [[Indonesia]]. Based on the 2015 estimate, it is Indonesia's fourth most populous city after [[Jakarta]], [[Surabaya]], and [[Bekasi]] with over 2.5 million inhabitants. [[Greater Bandung]] is the country's third-largest [[List of metropolitan areas in Indonesia|metropolitan area]] with over 8.5 million inhabitants.<ref>http://www.citypopulation.de/php/indonesia-jawa-admin.php</ref> Located {{convert|768|m|abbr=off}} [[above sea level]], approximately {{convert|140|km|0|abbr=off}} southeast of [[Jakarta]], Bandung has cooler year-round temperatures than most other [[List of cities in Indonesia|Indonesian cities]]. The city lies on a [[river basin]] surrounded by [[volcano|volcanic]] mountains that provides a natural defence system, which was the primary reason for the [[Dutch East Indies]] government's plan to move the capital from Batavia (modern-day [[Jakarta]]) to Bandung.\n\nThe Dutch first established tea [[plantation]]s around the mountains in the 18th century, and a road was constructed to connect the plantation area to the colonial capital [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] ({{convert|180|km|0|abbr=off}} to the northwest). In the early 20th century the Dutch inhabitants of Bandung demanded the establishment of a municipality (''gemeente''), which was granted in 1906, and Bandung gradually developed into a resort city for plantation owners. Luxurious hotels, restaurants, caf\u00e9s, and European boutiques were opened, leading the city to be nicknamed ''Parijs van Java'' ({{lang-nl|\"The Paris of Java\"}}).\n\nAfter [[Indonesian Declaration of Independence|Indonesia declared independence]] in 1945, the city experienced has experienced ongoing development and urbanisation, transforming from an idyllic town into a dense 16,500 people/km<sup>2</sup> (per square kilometre) metropolitan area with living space for over 8 million people. New [[skyscraper]]s, high-rise buildings, bridges, and gardens have been constructed. [[Natural resource]]s have been heavily exploited, particularly by conversion of the protected upland area into highland villas and real estate. Although the city has encountered many problems (ranging from waste disposal and floods, to a complicated traffic system resulting from a lack of road infrastructure), it still attracts large numbers of tourists, weekend sightseers, and migrants from other parts of Indonesia. In 2017 the city won a regional environmental sustainability award for having the cleanest air among major cities in [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|ASEAN]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jakartaglobe.id/news/bandung-wins-cleanest-air-award-asean/|title=Bandung Wins Cleanest Air Award From Asean|newspaper=Jakarta Globe|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> The city is also known as a [[Smart City]], leveraging technology to improve government services and social media, that alert residents to issues such as floods or traffic jams.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chandran|first1=Nyshka|title=Architect-turned-mayor transforms his hometown into Indonesia's least bureaucratic city|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/13/indonesian-city-of-bandung-capitalizes-on-smart-technology-under-mayor-ridwan-kamil.html|accessdate=24 January 2018|publisher=CNBC|date=13 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Valentina|first1=Jessicha|title=Bandung is Indonesia's leading smart city: Eco-architect|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/life/2017/03/02/bandung-is-indonesias-leading-smart-city-eco-architect.html|accessdate=24 January 2018|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|date=March 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first Asian-African Conference, the [[Bandung Conference]], was hosted in Bandung by President [[Sukarno]] in 1955. Redevelopment of the existing [[Husein Sastranegara International Airport|Bandung international airport]] (BDO) was completed in 2016. To improve infrastructure, the construction of a Jakarta-Bandung [[High-speed rail]] was started in 2016, with projected completion in 2020. This is to be complemented by an indigenous type of [[people mover|Automated People Mover]] (APM) and [[light rail transit|Light Rail Transit]] (LRT).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://berita.suaramerdeka.com/bandung-segera-miliki-metro-kapsul/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204004502/http://berita.suaramerdeka.com/bandung-segera-miliki-metro-kapsul/ |archive-date=4 February 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>https://bisnis.tempo.co/read/1282014/pt-kai-mulai-garap-pengumpan-kereta-cepat-jakarta-bandung</ref> The new larger second airport, Bandung [[Kertajati International Airport]], opened in June 2018.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Bandung}}\n[[File:Gedung.Merdeka.jpg|left|thumb|Gedung Merdeka (Independence Building) during the Asian-African Conference in 1955]]\nThe official name of the city during the colonial Dutch East Indies period was '''Bandoeng'''. The earliest reference to the area dates back to 1488, although archaeological findings suggest a type of ''[[Homo erectus]]'' species had long previously lived on the banks of the Cikapundung River and around the old lake of Bandung.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=B. Brahmantyo |author2=E. Yulianto and Sudjatmiko | title = On the geomorphological development of Pawon Cave, west of Bandung, and the evidence finding of prehistoric dwelling cave| journal = JTM| year = 2001| url = http://www.geocities.com/ekoy001/PawonJTM-web.htm| accessdate = 21 August 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080408111619/http://www.geocities.com/ekoy001/PawonJTM-web.htm|archivedate=8 April 2008}}</ref> During the 17th and 18th centuries, the [[Dutch East Indies Company]] (VOC) established plantations in the Bandung area. In 1786, a supply road connecting Batavia (now [[Jakarta]]), [[Bogor]], [[Cianjur]], Bandung, [[Sumedang]] and [[Cirebon]] was constructed. In 1809, [[Napoleon|Napoleon Bonaparte]], French Emperor and conqueror of much of Europe including the [[Netherlands]] and its colonies, ordered the Dutch Indies Governor [[Daendels|H.W. Daendels]] to improve the defensive systems of [[Java island|Java]] to protect against the British in India. Daendels built a road, stretching approximately {{convert|1,000|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the west to the east coast of Java, passing through Bandung.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pramoedya sheds light on dark side of Daendels highway|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|date=8 January 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Peter .J.M Nas |author2=Pratiwo |year=2001|publisher=University of Leiden|url=http://www.leidenuniv.nl/fsw/nas/pdf/NasPratiwoPostweg30-10-2001.pdf|format=PDF|title=Java and De Groote Postweg, La Grande Route, The High Military Road|accessdate=22 June 2009}}</ref> In 1810, the road was laid down in Bandung and was named ''De Groote Postweg'' (or the '[[Great Post Road]]'), the present-day location of Jalan Asia-Afrika. Under Daendels' orders, R. A. Wiranatakusumah II, the Chief Administrator of the Bandung regency at that time, moved the office from Krapyak, in the south, to a place near a pair of holy city wells (''sumur Bandung''), the present-day site of the city square (''alun-alun''). He built his ''dalem'' (palace), ''masjid agung'' (the grand mosque) and ''pendopo'' (public-official meeting place) in the classical Sundanese orientation,<ref>{{cite book|title=Wajah Bandung Tempoe Doeloe|author=Kunto, Haryanto|year=1984|publisher=Granesia}}</ref> with the pendopo facing [[Tangkuban Perahu]] mountain, which was believed to have a mystical ambience.\n\nIn 1880, the first major railroad between Batavia and Bandung was completed,<ref name=creative>{{cite conference|booktitle=The eleventh International Planning History Conference 2004 |title=Creative culture and urban planning: The Bandung Experience |first=Ahmad R. |last=Soemardi |author2=Radjawali, I |year=2004 |url=http://www.etsav.upc.es/personals/iphs2004/pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=21 August 2006 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> boosting light industry in Bandung. [[Overseas Chinese|Chinese]] flocked into the city to help run facilities, services and as vendors. The area adjacent to the train station is still recognisable as the old Chinatown district. In 1906, Bandung was given the status of ''gemeente'' (municipality), and then twenty years later, ''stadsgemeente'' (city municipality).\n\nBeginning of time the early 1920s, the Dutch East Indies government made plans to move their capital from Batavia to Bandung. Accordingly, during this decade, the Dutch colonial government commenced construction of military barracks, the central government building (''Gouvernments Bedrijven'', the present-day [[Gedung Sate]]) and other government buildings. However, this plan was cut short by [[World War II]], after which the Dutch were not able to re-establish their colony due to the Indonesian Declaration of Independence.\n\nThe fertile area of the Parahyangan Mountains surrounding Bandung supports productive [[tea]] plantations. In the nineteenth century, [[Franz Wilhelm Junghuhn|Franz Junghuhn]] introduced the [[cinchona]] (''kina'') plant.<ref>{{cite news|title=If Only Junghuhn Knows How Cinchona in Indonesia Becomes... |publisher=Pikiran Rakyat |language=Indonesian |url=http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/cetak/0604/07/0108.htm |date=7 June 2004 |accessdate=21 August 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060517024534/http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/cetak/0604/07/0108.htm |archivedate=17 May 2006 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> With its cooler elevated landscape, surrounded by major plantations, Bandung became an exclusive European resort area.<ref name=brief>{{cite web  | title = An Extremely Brief Urban History of Bandung | publisher = Institute of Indonesian Architectural Historian | url=http://www.iis.u-tokyo.ac.jp/~fujimori/lsai/bandung.html| accessdate = 20 August 2006 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060716093926/http://www.iis.u-tokyo.ac.jp/~fujimori/lsai/bandung.html| archivedate= 16 July 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref> Wealthy plantation owners visited the city on weekends, attracting ladies and business people from the capital, Batavia. [[Braga Street|Jalan Braga]] grew into a promenade street with caf\u00e9s, restaurants and boutique shops. Two [[art-deco]] style hotels, Savoy Homann and Preanger, were built in the vicinity of the Concordia Society, a clubhouse for the wealthy with a large ballroom and a theatre.<ref name=creative/>\n\nAfter [[Indonesian Declaration of Independence|Indonesian independence]] in 1945, Bandung was designated as the capital of [[West Java]] [[province]]. During the [[Indonesian National Revolution]], some of the most massive battles occurred in and around Bandung. Dutch troops were virtually absent in Java at the end of World War II. To assist the restoration of Dutch sovereignty, the [[United Kingdom|British]] took a military hold on Java's major cities, and the British military commander set an ultimatum for the Indonesian combatants in Bandung to leave the city. In response, on 24 March 1946, much of the southern part of Bandung was deliberately set alight as the combatants left; an event known as ''Bandung Lautan Api'' or the '[[Bandung Sea of Fire]]'.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.bandungheritage.org/images/stories/dokumen/bandung_sea_of_fire.pdf |format=PDF |title=Social History of Bandung Lautan Api (Bandung Sea of Fire) 24 March 1946 |author=Sitaresmi, Ratnayu |accessdate=22 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603233047/http://www.bandungheritage.org/images/stories/dokumen/bandung_sea_of_fire.pdf |archivedate=3 June 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1955, the first Asian-African Conference, also known as the ''[[Bandung Conference]]'', was hosted in Bandung by President [[Sukarno]], and attended by the heads of states representing twenty-nine independent countries from Asia and Africa.<ref>Jamie Mackie, 'Bandung 1955: Non-Alignment and Afro-Asian Solidarity', [[Singapore]], Editions Didier Millet, {{ISBN|981-4155-49-7}}</ref> The conference venue was at the [[Gedung Merdeka]], the former Concordia Society building. The conference announced ten points of declaration for the promotion of [[world peace]] and opposition against [[colonialism]] and is known as the [[Bandung Conference#Declaration|Declaration of Bandung]]. This was followed by a wave of nationalism and [[decolonisation]] movements around the globe which remapped world politics.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Cold War II: The Eisenhower Administration, the Bandung Conference, and the Reperiodization of the Postwar Era| author=Jason Parker| journal=Diplomatic History| volume=30| issue=5| year=2006| pages=867\u2013892| doi=10.1111/j.1467-7709.2006.00582.x}}</ref> The conference was also the first international conference of people of colour in history.<ref name=\"wright\">{{cite book|title=The Color Curtain: A Report on the Bandung Conference| author=Richard Wright| authorlink=Richard Wright (author)| publisher=University Press of Mississippi |year=1995|isbn=0-87805-748-X}}</ref> In his book ''[[The Color Curtain]]'', [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]] claims that there was an epic meaning of the conference for people of colour around the world.<ref name=\"wright\"/>\n\nIn 1987, the city boundary was expanded by the 'Greater Bandung' (''Bandung Raya'') plan; with the relocation of higher concentration development zones outside the city in an attempt to dilute population density in the old city. During this development, the [[city centre|city core]] was often uprooted, with old buildings torn down, lot sizes regrouped and rezoned, changing idyllic residential areas to commercial zones with bustling chain supermarkets, malls, banks and upscale developments.<ref name=brief/>\n\nIn 2005, an Asian-African Conference was partly held in Bandung, attended by world leaders such as Indonesian President Susilo B. Yudhoyono, President of [[China]] Hu Jintao, Prime Minister of [[India]] Manmohan Singh, President of [[South Africa]] Thabo Mbeki, President of [[Nigeria]] Obasanjo, and other luminaries.<ref name=\"Discover Bandung\">[http://discoverbandung.chasecareer.net Discover Bandung] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307003733/http://discoverbandung.chasecareer.net/ |date=7 March 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Cekungan Bandung.jpg|alt=Bandung Basin|thumb|right|Bandung Basin]]\nBandung, the capital of [[West Java]] province, located about {{convert|180|km|mi}} southeast of [[Jakarta]], is the third-largest city in [[Indonesia]]. Its elevation is {{convert|768|m|ft}} [[above sea level]] and is surrounded by up to {{convert|2400|m|abbr=off}} high [[Tertiary|Late Tertiary]] and [[Quaternary]] volcanic terrain.<ref name=\"Kaars95\">{{cite journal|title=A 135,000-year record of vegetational and climatic change from the Bandung area, West-Java, Indonesia| journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|volume=117|issue=1\u20132|pages=55\u201372|year=1995|doi=10.1016/0031-0182(94)00121-N|author1=W.A. van der Kaars  |author2=M.A.C. Dam  |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>  The 400&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> flat of central Bandung plain is situated in the middle of {{convert|2,340.88|km2}} wide of the Bandung [[Drainage basin|Basin]]; the basin comprises Bandung, the [[Cimahi]] city, part of [[Bandung Regency]], part of [[West Bandung]] Regency, and part of [[Sumedang Regency]].<ref name=\"iges\">{{cite conference| author = Setiawan Wangsaatmaja, Arief D. Sutadian and Maria A.N. Prasetiati| title = Groundwater Resource Management in Bandung| booktitle = Sustainable Groundwater Management in Asian Cities| publisher = Institute for Global Environmental Strategies| url = http://www.iges.or.jp/en/fw/report01.html| accessdate = 21 August 2006| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060902174254/http://www.iges.or.jp/en/fw/report01.html| archivedate = 2 September 2006| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> The basin's main river is the [[Citarum river|Citarum]]; one of its branches, the [[Cikapundung River|Cikapundung]], divides Bandung from north to south before it merges with Citarum again in Dayeuhkolot. The Bandung Basin is an essential source of water for potable water, irrigation, and fisheries, with its {{convert|6,147|e6m3|abbr=unit}} of groundwater being a significant reservoir for the city.<ref name=\"iges\"/>\nThe northern section of Bandung is hillier than other parts of the city, and the unique truncated flat-peak shape of the [[Mount Tangkuban Perahu|Tangkuban Perahu]] volcano (''Tangkuban Perahu'' literally means 'upside-down boat') can be seen from the city to the north. Long-term volcanic activity has created fertile [[andisols|andisol]] soil in the north, suitable for intensive [[rice]], [[fruit]], [[tea]], [[tobacco]], and [[coffee]] plantations. In the [[south]] and [[east]], [[alluvial]] soils deposited by the Cikapundung river predominate.\n\nGeological data shows that the Bandung Basin is located on an ancient volcano, known as [[Mount Sunda]], erected up to {{convert|3,000|-|4,000|m|abbr=off}} during the [[Pleistocene]] age.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=M.N. Kartadinata |author2=M. Okuno |author3=T. Nakamura |author4=T. Kobayashi |title=Eruptive History of Tangkuban Perahu Volcano, West Java, Indonesia: A Preliminary Report |journal=Journal of Geography |volume=111 |issue=3 |pages=404\u2013409 |year=2002 |url=http://www.geog.or.jp/journal/back/pdf111-3/p404-409.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=21 August 2006 |doi=10.5026/jgeography.111.3_404 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060823232638/http://www.geog.or.jp/journal/back/pdf111-3/p404-409.pdf |archivedate=23 August 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Two large-scale eruptions took place; the first formed the basin and the second (est. 55,000 BCE) blocked the Citarum river, turning the basin into a lake known as \"the Great Prehistoric Lake of Bandung\".<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Dam, M.A.C. | title = The Late Quaternary Evolution of the [[Bandung Basin]], West Java, Indonesia | version = Ph.D. Thesis| publisher = Universiteit van Amsterdam| year = 1994}}</ref> The lake drained away; for reasons which are the subject of ongoing debate among geologists.<ref>{{cite book| last = van Bemmelen| first = R.W.| title = The Geology of Indonesia, Vol. 1A, General Geology| year = 1949}}</ref><ref name=\"sangiangtikoro\">{{cite news|title=Sangiangtikoro is not The Leaking Point of The Old Bandung Lake |language=Indonesian |publisher=Pikiran Rakyat |date=27 October 2005 |url=http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/cetak/2005/0905/27/0108.htm |accessdate=20 July 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929120458/http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/cetak/2005/0905/27/0108.htm |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nBandung experiences [[tropical monsoon climate]] (''Am'') according to [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] as the driest month precipitation total is below {{convert|60|mm}}, bordering with [[subtropical highland climate]] (''Cfb''). The wettest month is February with precipitation total {{convert|255.0|mm}}, while the driest month is September with precipitation total {{convert|50.0|mm}}. The average temperature throughout the year tends to be cooler than most cities in Indonesia due to the altitude influence. The average temperature throughout the year only has little variation due to its location near the equator.\n{{Weather box|location=[[Husein Sastranegara International Airport]], Bandung, West Java, Indonesia (temperature: 1972-1994, precipitation: 1957-1994)|metric first=yes|single line=yes|Jan record high C=32.2|Feb record high C=31.1|Mar record high C=32.2|Apr record high C=30.6|May record high C=31.1|Jun record high C=30.6|Jul record high C=30.6|Aug record high C=31.1|Sep record high C=32.8|Oct record high C=34.4|Nov record high C=33.9|Dec record high C=31.1|Jan high C=27.2|Feb high C=26.7|Mar high C=27.2|Apr high C=27.8|May high C=27.8|Jun high C=27.8|Jul high C=27.8|Aug high C=28.3|Sep high C=28.9|Oct high C=28.9|Nov high C=27.8|Dec high C=27.2|year high C=27.8|Jan mean C=23.3|Feb mean C=23.1|Mar mean C=23.3|Apr mean C=23.6|May mean C=23.3|Jun mean C=22.8|Jul mean C=22.5|Aug mean C=22.8|Sep mean C=23.3|Oct mean C=23.6|Nov mean C=23.3|Dec mean C=23.3|year mean C=23.2|Jan low C=19.4|Feb low C=19.4|Mar low C=19.4|Apr low C=19.4|May low C=18.9|Jun low C=17.8|Jul low C=17.2|Aug low C=17.2|Sep low C=17.8|Oct low C=18.3|Nov low C=18.9|Dec low C=19.4|year low C=18.6|Jan record low C=15.0|Feb record low C=15.6|Mar record low C=15.0|Apr record low C=13.9|May record low C=13.9|Jun record low C=11.7|Jul record low C=11.1|Aug record low C=11.7|Sep record low C=11.7|Oct record low C=13.9|Nov record low C=12.8|Dec record low C=15.0|precipitation colour=green|Jan precipitation mm=240.0|Feb precipitation mm=255.0|Mar precipitation mm=239.0|Apr precipitation mm=143.0|May precipitation mm=116.1|Jun precipitation mm=102.1|Jul precipitation mm=69.1|Aug precipitation mm=56.9|Sep precipitation mm=50.0|Oct precipitation mm=151.1|Nov precipitation mm=200.9|Dec precipitation mm=215.1\n|Jan sun = 155\n|Feb sun = 168\n|Mar sun = 186\n|Apr sun = 210\n|May sun = 217\n|Jun sun = 240\n|Jul sun = 248\n|Aug sun = 248\n|Sep sun = 210\n|Oct sun = 217\n|Nov sun = 180\n|Dec sun = 186\n|year sun =\n|Jand sun = 5.0\n|Febd sun = 6.0\n|Mard sun = 6.0\n|Aprd sun = 7.0\n|Mayd sun = 7.0\n|Jund sun = 8.0\n|Juld sun = 8.0\n|Augd sun = 8.0\n|Sepd sun = 7.0\n|Octd sun = 7.0\n|Novd sun = 6.0\n|Decd sun = 6.0\n\n|source 1=Sistema de Clasificaci\u00f3n Bioclim\u00e1tica Mundial<ref name=climate>\n{{cite web\n| url = http://www.globalbioclimatics.org/station/in-husei.htm\n| title = INDONESIA - HUSEIN SASTRANEG\n| publisher = Centro de Investigaciones Fitosociol\u00f3gicas\n| accessdate = 26 June 2016}}\n|</ref>\n|source 2 = Weather Atlas (sunshine data)<ref name=\"Weather Atlas\">{{cite web |url=https://www.weather-atlas.com/en/indonesia/bandung-climate|title=Bandung, Indonesia - Monthly weather forecast and Climate data |publisher=Weather Atlas |access-date=24 January 2019 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Environmental issues===\nThe north of the city serves as a [[water reservoir]] for Bandung. However, the area has seen substantial residential development. Several attempts to protect this area have been made, including the creation of reserves such as the Juanda National Park and Puncrut, but development continues. Regular flooding in Bandung's south also presents a real and dangerous ongoing problem.<ref>{{cite conference| first = Agus| last = Fahmudin|author2=Wahyunto| title = Evaluation of Flood Mitigation Function of Several Land Use Systems in Selected Areas of West Java, Indonesia| booktitle = Japan / OECD Expert Meeting on Land Conservation Indicators| publisher = OECD| url = http://www.olis.oecd.org/comnet/agr/landconserv.nsf/viewHtml/index/$FILE/Fahmuddin.PDF| format = PDF}}</ref>\n\nFrom mid-2005, Bandung faced another environmental disaster, when the city's [[landfill]] site was reevaluated after a garbage slide in 2005 which buried a village, Kampung Gajah, beneath it, killing over a hundred people.<ref>SP 18 May 2006 http://www.sp18.com/2006/05/</ref> The accumulation of {{convert|8,000|m3/day|abbr=on}} of domestic garbage piled up, causes severe air pollution by local burning, the spread of disease, and water contamination. The provincial government has so far failed in its attempts to solve the garbage issue.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trash in Bandung Fears Uncollected|publisher=Pikiran Rakyat|language=Indonesian|url=http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/cetak/2005/0205/23/0103.htm|date=23 February 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=From Bandung Ocean of Flame to the Ocean of Trash |newspaper=Kompas |language=Indonesian |url=http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0503/14/teropong/1615278.htm |date=25 March 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625071739/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0503/14/teropong/1615278.htm |archivedate=25 June 2013 }}</ref> Nevertheless, it was awarded in 1997 and 2015 as the least polluted city in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Pemkot Bandung Berupaya Raih Kembali Adipura|url = http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/bandung-raya/2014/11/13/304457/pemkot-bandung-berupaya-raih-kembali-adipura|website = Pikiran Rakyat Online|accessdate = 2016-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Kota Bandung Raih Penghargaan Adipura :: Bandung.go.id {{!}} Portal Resmi Kota Bandung|url = http://portal.bandung.go.id/kota-bandung-raih-penghargaan-adipura|website = portal.bandung.go.id|accessdate = 2016-01-08}}</ref> Further, a regional award in 2017 was also given from ASEAN as the cleanest air among other major cities in ASEAN countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jakartaglobe.id/news/bandung-wins-cleanest-air-award-asean/ |title=Bandung Wins Cleanest Air Award From Asean |accessdate=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n[[File:Gedung Sate Bandung.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sate]] Building, Bandung]]\nThe city area in 1906 was {{convert|19.22|km2|2|abbr=off}} and by 1987, it had expanded to 167.2965&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=\"bda2003\">{{cite press release|publisher=Bureau of Statistics|title=''Bandung Dalam Angka'' (Bandung in Numbers)|year=2003| url=http://www.bandung.go.id/index.php?fa=download.category&id=1&startpage=1&offset=0| language=Indonesian|accessdate=15 January 2007}}</ref> The city administration is divided into 30 [[Districts of Indonesia|districts]] (''kecamatan'') and 153 [[Villages of Indonesia|villages]] (''kelurahan''). For development purposes, the 30 districts are grouped into eight sub-city regions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://data.bandung.go.id/dataset/data-spasial-sub-wilayah-kota-bandung|title=Data Spasial Sub Wilayah Kota Bandung|last=Dinas Penataan Ruang Kota Bandung|first=|date=2017-02-10|website=Portal Data Bandung|access-date=}}</ref> The sub-city regions of Bandung are Arcamanik, Cibeunying, Kerees, Kordon, Gedebage, Ujungberung, Bojonagara and Tegalega. The mayor (''walikota'') - [[Oded Muhammad Danial]] since 2018 - leads the city administration. Since 2008, city residents have directly voted for a mayor; previously mayors were nominated and selected by the city council - the Regional People's Representative Council (DPRD) which has 50 members. As of 2003, the total number of city administration personnel was 20,163.<ref name=\"bda2003\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Keanggotaan DPRD Kota Bandung Periode 2014-2019 \u2013 DPRD KOTA BANDUNG |url=https://dprd.bandung.go.id/keanggotaan-dprd-kota-bandung-periode-2014-2019/ |publisher=Bandung City Council |accessdate=26 March 2019 |language=id-ID}}</ref>\n\nBandung City is divided into 30 [[Districts of Indonesia|districts]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pn-bandung.go.id/uploads/file/DataKelKec.pdf |title=: DATA KECAMATAN DI LINGKUNGAN PEMERINTAH KOTA BANDUNG: Berdasarkan PERDA 2008 |access-date=1 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013133229/http://pn-bandung.go.id/uploads/file/DataKelKec.pdf |archive-date=13 October 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (''kecamatan''), listed below with their populations at the 2010 Census:<ref>Biro Pusat Statistik, Jakarta, 2011.</ref>\n\n{{Col-begin|width=90%}}\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Arcamanik region'''\n* Antapani (72,006)\n* Arcamanik (65,607)\n* Mandalajati (60,825)\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Bojonagara region'''\n* Andir (94,361)\n* Cicendo (96,491)\n* Sukajadi (104,805)\n* Sukasari (79,211)\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Cibeunying region'''\n* Bandung Wetan (29,807)\n* Cibeunying Kaler (68,807)\n* Cibeunying Kidul (104,575)\n* Cidadap (56,325)\n* Coblong (127,588)\n* Sumur Bandung (34,486)\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Gedebage region'''\n* Gedebage (34,299)\n* Rancasari (72,406)\n{{col-end}}\n\n{{Col-begin|width=90%}}\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Karees region'''\n* Batununggal (116,935)\n* Kiaracondong (127,616)\n* Lengkong (69,307)\n* Regol (79,316)\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Kordon region'''\n* Bandung Kidul (57,398)\n* Buahbatu (92,140)\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Tegalega region'''\n* Astanaanyar (66,658)\n* Babakan Ciparay (143,203)\n* Bandung Kulon (138,644)\n* Bojongloa Kaler (117,218)\n* Bojongloa Kidul (83,600)\n{{Col-break}}\n'''Ujungberung region'''\n* [[Cibiru]] (67,412)\n* Cinambo (23,762)\n* Panyileukan (37,691)\n* Ujung Berung (72,414)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Economy==\nThe city's economy is mainly built upon tourism, business, creative industry, high-tech and manufacturing industries, educational institutions, technology, retail services, financial services, pharmaceutical companies, and food production.<ref name=\"Discover Bandung\"/> The once quiet residential district of Dago has become an important business and entertainment centre with chic caf\u00e9s and restaurants spread out along Jalan Dago. In the early 1990s, Jalan Cihampelas became a popular clothing store location, and remains so today.\n\nCreative culture has shaped specific parts of the city's economy. Small businesses, known as \"distro\", sell non-[[trademark]]ed products made by local designers. Books, indie label records, magazines, fashion products, and other accessories are typical distro products. Distros are popular with young people and distance themselves from factory outlets in term of [[philosophy]]. They arise from individual designers and young entrepreneurs, while factory outlet products generally come from large-scale garment factories.<ref>{{cite news|title=From Indie to Magic |url=http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0308/22/muda/504835.htm |language=Indonesian |newspaper=Kompas |date=22 August 2003 |accessdate=21 August 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929134336/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0308/22/muda/504835.htm |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe city administration has agreed to substantially develop seven industrial and trade areas for Bandung speciality products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/179610 |title=Tujuh Sentra Industri Jadi Ciri Bandung 2013 |date=6 March 2012}}</ref> These include Binong Jati Knitting Industrial and Trade Center, Cigondewah Textile Trade Center, Cihampelas Jeans Trade Center, Suci (T and Oblong) Shirt Industrial Center, Cibaduyut Shoes Industrial Center, Cibuntu Tofu and Tempeh Industrial Center, Sukamulya Sukajadi Doll Industrial Center.\n\nThe city is part of the [[Creative Cities Network|UNESCO Creative Cities Network]] which it joined in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aseaneconomist.com/unesco-names-singapore-and-bandung-as-creative-cities-of-design/|title=Unesco names Singapore and Bandung as Creative Cities of Design - Asean Economist|last=Rivers|first=Paul|date=2015-12-13|work=Asean Economist|access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2005, the population of Bandung was 2.2 million people with a density of {{pop density|13693|1.000|km2|sqmi}}.<ref>[http://www.indonesia.go.id/id/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2566&Itemid=1347 Profil Daerah Jawa Barat] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230234603/http://www.indonesia.go.id/id/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2566&Itemid=1347 |date=30 December 2013 }}</ref> The May 2010 census enumerated 2.3 million people.<ref>http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/bandung/2010/09/01/brk,20100901-275625,id.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531185243/http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/bandung/2010/09/01/brk,20100901-275625,id.html |date=31 May 2014 }} TempoInteraktif: Bandung Kota Terpadat di Jawa Barat</ref> Based on data from [[Statistics Indonesia]], the population of Bandung in 2014 was 2.4 million,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://bandungkota.bps.go.id/linkTableDinamis/view/id/9|title = Jumlah Pendududuk Menurut Jenis Kelamin Dan Kecamatan Di Kota Bandung 2011-2014|accessdate = 5 December 2015|website = Badan Pusat Statistik Kota Bandung|publisher = Badan Pusat Statistik Kota Bandung}}</ref> making Bandung the third most populous city in [[Indonesia]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!2005\n!2010\n!2014\n|-\n|Population\n|2,290,464\n|2,394,873\n|2,470,802\n|-\n|Population density (per km<sup>2</sup>)\n|13,660\n|14,283\n|14,736\n|}\nThe majority of Bandung's population are of [[Sundanese people|Sundanese]] descent. [[Javanese people|Javanese]] are the largest minority and mostly come from the [[Central Java|central]] and [[East Java|the eastern parts of Java]]. Other minorities include [[Minangkabau people|Minang]], [[Minahasan people|Minahasan]], [[Chinese Indonesians|Chinese]], [[Batak]], [[Malay Indonesian|Malay]], [[Koreans|Korean]], [[Indian people|Indian]], and [[Japanese people|Japanese]]. Bandung also possesses significant international communities, compared with other Indonesian cities.\n\n==Culture==\nBandung is a significant cultural hub in Indonesia. Most people in the surrounding province of West Java are [[Sundanese people|ethnically Sundanese]], with [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]] often spoken as a first language, as well as the common and informal language for communication in streets, school, work, and markets. As in the rest of the country, [[Indonesian language|standard Indonesian]] serves as the ''lingua franca'' and primary language of government, business, media, and formal education.\n\n===Architecture===\n{{See also|Indonesian architecture|List of colonial buildings in Bandung}}\n[[File:COLLECTIE TROPENMUSEUM Hotel Savoy Homann TMnr 20025485.jpg|upright|thumb|The Savoy homann hotel architectural design by [[Albert Aalbers]] in 1939 is one of the most significant examples of the Art Deco style for which Bandung is renowned]]\nBandung is home to numerous examples of Dutch colonial architecture; most notably the tropical Art Deco, dubbed [[New Indies Style]]. [[Henri Maclaine Pont]] was among the first Dutch architects to recognise the importance of combining each architectural style with local cultural traditions. He stressed that [[modern architecture]] should interact with [[local history]] and native elements.<ref name=\"ww\">{{cite conference|author1=W. Wangsadinata |author2=T.K. Djajasudarma |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Architectural Design Consideration for Modern Buildings in Indonesia |year=1995 |booktitle=INDOBEX Conf. on Building Construction Technology for the Future: Construction Technology for Highrises & Intelligence Buildings |location=[[Jakarta]] |url=http://www.wiratman.co.id/ximages/architecture.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=18 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070614232909/http://www.wiratman.co.id/ximages/architecture.pdf |archivedate=14 June 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 1920, Pont planned and designed buildings for the first technical university in the [[Dutch East Indies]], ''Technische Hogeschool te Bandung'' (the present-day [[Bandung Institute of Technology]]), after which he was named as a Professor of Architecture at the university. A striking local Sundanese roof style is clearly seen adorning the top of the campus' ceremonial hall and is embedded in his artwork.<ref name=\"ww\"/>\n\nIn the same year, another Dutch architect J Gerber designed ''Gouverments Bedrijven'' (Government Companies) in line with the colonial government plan to move the capital from Batavia to Bandung. The building is an example of a harmonious mixture between West and East architectural styles, particularly the [[Italian Renaissance]] style of [[arch]] structures in the wings and [[pendopo]]-like structures commonly found in Java in the middle section. The building is known as [[Gedung Sate]], named after the distinguished small [[satay]]-shaped structure on the roof, and is today used as the head office of the [[West Java]] provincial government and House of Representatives.\n\nThe architectural blending of modern and native traditional was followed by several Dutch architects who shaped the city landmarks. In the 1930s, Bandung became known as an architectural laboratory due to the many Dutch architects who experimented with new architectural designs. [[Albert Aalbers]] added the [[streamline moderne]] style to the Art Deco by designing the DENIS bank (1936) and renovated the Savoy Homann Hotel (1939). [[Charles Prosper Wolff Schoemaker]] was one of the architects who strongly added native elements in his artworks, including the [[Villa Isola]] (1932), Hotel Preanger (1929), the regional military headquarter (1918), [[Gedung Merdeka]] (1921) and ITB Rectorate Building (1925).<ref name=\"ww\"/>\n\n[[File:Bandung Cathedral Indonesia.jpg|Bandung Cathedral|upright|thumb|right|Bandung [[Cathedral]], seat of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Bandung]]]]\nThough Bandung is known for its large number of old Dutch architecture buildings, the city is going through a high-rise building boom recently. At present, there are more than 100 high rise building in the city and many more under construction or planned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/city/100261/bandung-indonesia/type/3/1|title=High-rise buildings in Bandung}}</ref> The following list includes buildings in Bandung, which are completed or topped off and which are above 300&nbsp;ft 91 metres.\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n! Rank!! Name !! Floors !!Height<br /><small>m</small> !!Year!!Image!!Note\n|-\n|1||Galeri Cimbuleuit 2||36||141||2014||||At present the tallest building in Bandung<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1201708/galeri-cimbuleuit-2-bandung-indonesia|title=Galeri Cimbuleuit 2}}</ref>\n|-\n|2||Parahyangan Residences A||35 ||130 ||2016||||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1201714/parahyangan-residences-a-bandung-indonesia|title=Parahyangan Residences A}}</ref>\n|-\n|3||Newton The Hybrid Park Apartment A|| 32 ||121||2016||||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1201709/newton-the-hybrid-park-apartment-a-bandung-indonesia|title=Newton The Hybrid Park Apartment A}}</ref>\n|-\n|4||Tamansari Panoramic Apartment||30||115||2014||||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1201716/tamansari-panoramic-apartment-bandung-indonesia|title=Tamansari Panoramic Apartment}}</ref> \n|-\n|5||Ibis Hotel Bandung||24||111||2011||||\n|-\n|6||Newton The Hybrid Park Apartment B|| 30||110||2016||||\n|-\n|7||Harris Hotel Ciumbuleuit||28||110||2014||||\n|-\n|8||Crowne Plaza Hotel||21||109||2014||||\n|-\n|10||Apartemen Galeri Ciumbuleuit III|| 30||106||2016||||\n|-\n|11||The Trans Luxury Hotel||20||101||2012||||\n|-\n|12||Newton Hybrid Park III|| 26||98||2017||||\n|-\n|13||The Jarrdin @Cihampelas Apartment I||25||98||2013||||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/complex/129056/the-jarrdin-apartment-bandung-indonesia|title=The Jarrdin Apartment}}</ref>\n|-\n|14||The Jarrdin @Cihampelas Apartment II||25||98||2013||||\n|-\n|15||The Jarrdin @Cihampelas Apartment III||25||98||2013||||\n|-\n|16||The Jarrdin @Cihampelas Apartment IV||25||98||2013||||\n|-\n|17||Grand Asia Afrika Residence A||24||94||2016||||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/1201723/grand-asia-afrika-apartment-a-bandung-indonesia|title=Grand Asia Afrika Residence A}}</ref>\n|-\n|18||Grand Asia Afrika Residence B||24||94||2016||||\n|-\n|19||Gateway Apartment A||23||91||2013||||\n|-\n|20||Gateway Apartment B||23||91||2012||||\n|-\n|21||Sudirman Suites Apartment||22||||||||\n|-\n|22||Apartemen Galeri Ciumbuleuit||22||||2005||||\n|-\n|}\n{{Wide image|Bandung City Centre - Evening - panoramio.jpg|1080px|Night view of Bandung city center}}\n\n===Tourism===\n[[File:Denim store, Cihampelas Street, Bandung.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Denim]] store, Cihampelas Street]]\nBandung is a popular [[weekend]] destination for residents of [[Jakarta]]. The colder climate of the highland plantation area, variety of food, less expensive [[fashion]] shops located in factory outlets and [[Bandung#Economy|distros]], golf courses, and the [[Bandung Zoo|zoo]], are some of the attractions of the city.<ref>Java Experience http://travel.ciao.co.uk/Java_Experience_5297272_5 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060508000354/http://travel.ciao.co.uk/Java_Experience_5297272_5 |date=8 May 2006 }}</ref> Bandung is also a popular shopping destination due to the cheap textile and fashion products, especially for [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] and [[Singaporean people|Singaporean]] tourists.<ref>[http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/07/16/malaysians-flock-bandung-shop.html Malaysians flock to Bandung to shop]</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, local designers opened denim clothing stores along Jalan Cihampelas, which was transformed into a \"jeans street\". The city attracts people from other big cities to buy local fashion wares, as they are cheaper than branded items.<ref>Asia Travel http://www.asiatravel.com/bandinfo.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060828161046/http://asiatravel.com/bandinfo.html |date=28 August 2006 }}</ref> Beside Jalan Cihampelas, many factory outlets also opened at Jalan Riau, Jalan Setiabudi, and Jalan [[Djuanda]]  (known as [[Dago, Indonesia|Dago]]). Textile factories on the outskirts of Bandung have opened factory outlets on site selling what is marketed as ''sisa export'' (rejected or over-produced export quality items).<ref>The Lively Pulse of Bandung {{cite web|url=http://www.thingsasian.com/goto_article/article.2543.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-08-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427183652/http://www.thingsasian.com/goto_article/article.2543.html |archivedate=27 April 2006 }}</ref> [[Trans Studio Bandung|Trans Studio Mall]], [[:id:Bandung Indah Plaza|Bandung Indah Plaza]], [[:id:Cihampelas Walk|Cihampelas Walk]], [[:id:Paris Van Java Mall|Paris Van Java Mall]] and [[:id:23 Paskal Shopping Center|23 Paskal Shopping Center]] are among the popular shopping centres in Bandung.\n\nSignificant tourist sites near Bandung include the [[Tangkuban Prahu]] volcano crater to the north, the [[Kawah Putih]] volcano lake, and [[Patenggang Lake]], a lake surrounded by tea plantations about {{convert|50|km|0|abbr=off}} to the south of the city.\n\nTo view the Bandung Basin clearly in its mountain surroundings, visitors travel to the Bongkor protected forest area (kawasan hutan lindung), Saung Daweung and Arcamanik; to the slopes of West Manglayang Mountain in an area known as Caringin Tilu, with entry from Padasuka and Cicaheum to the north. The forest is located in {{convert|1,500|m|ft|lk=out|abbr=off}} [[above sea level]] and is covered with pine trees managed by a government corporation [[:id:Perhutani|Perhutani]] and can be accessed with 30 minutes drive from downtown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bumn.go.id/perhutani/berita/0-Pinus-yang-Mengiurkan |title=Pinus yang Mengiurkan |date=21 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2014/09/01/199603525/The-Wind-Breeze-of-Bongkor-Forest |title=The Wind Breeze of Bongkor Forest |date=1 September 2014}}</ref> Visitors going to the north of the city also find [[Taman Hutan Raya Ir. H. Djuanda]]. The Cicaheum area also hosts ''Bukit Moko'', a tourist spot famous for its views and its steel statue of a giant star called ''Puncak Bintang''. Bandung has several museums that should be visited by tourists, such as the [[Geological Museum of Bandung]], the [[:id:Museum Pos|Indonesia Postal Museum]], [[Sri Baduga Museum]], and the [[Merdeka Building|Asian-African Conference Museum]].\n\n{{Wide image|Floating Market Lembang - including selfie alays (27126485005).jpg|900px|Floating market where local foods, snacks & items like clothing are carried by sellers on boats.|}}\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Peparnas XV.jpg|thumb|Opening [[National Sports Week (Indonesia)#Pekan Paralimpik Nasional|National Paralympic Week]] 2016 (XV) in [[Siliwangi Stadium]].]]\nBandung is the home of [[Persib Bandung]], a professional football club currently competing in the highest tier of Indonesian football, the ''[[Liga 1 (Indonesia)|Liga 1]]''. The JNE Bandung Utama competes in the [[Indonesian Basketball League]], with its home games in the ''GOR Citra Arena''. The roads leading up to [[Lembang]] and [[Dago, Bandung|Dago]] are popular routes for mountain [[cycling]] on weekends, as Jalan Ir. H. Djuanda is zoned as [[Pedestrian zone|car-free]] on Sunday mornings.<ref>http://www.bandungview.info/2013/10/car-free-day-dago.html</ref> \n\nOther popular sports in Bandung include [[badminton]] and [[golf]], with several [[golf courses]] surrounding the city.\n\n===Media===\n{{See also|List of radio stations in Bandung, Indonesia}}\n\nBandung has several local daily newspapers, including ''[[Pikiran Rakyat]]'', ''Galamedia'', and ''Tribun Jabar''. Several national and local television stations operate in Bandung, including [[Trans 7]], [[Trans TV]], [[NET.]], [[tvOne (Indonesia)|tvOne]], [[RCTI]], [[SCTV (Indonesia)|SCTV]], [[Indosiar]], [[ANTV]], [[MNCTV]], [[GTV (Indonesia)|GTV]], [[Metro TV (Indonesia)|Metro TV]], [[Rajawali Televisi|RTV Bandung]], [[Kompas TV|Kompas TV Jawa Barat]], and [[TVRI]]. Many radio stations, such as INTV Bandung, [[List of radio stations in Bandung, Indonesia|also broadcast from Bandung]].\n\n[[Cable TV|Cable]] is widely available by several service providers serving international channels such as [[CNN]], [[BBC]], [[Fox (channel)|Fox]], [[MTV]], [[CNBC]], [[Bloomberg TV Indonesia|Bloomberg Indonesia]], [[CGTN]], [[NHK]], [[Special Broadcasting Service]], [[Channel NewsAsia]], and others.\n\nThe city of Bandung was featured in the 9th and 10th leg of the American reality series ''[[The Amazing Race 23]]''.\n\n==Transport==\n===Road===\n[[File:Angkot Bandung Sadang Serang-Caringin.jpg|thumb|An ''angkot'' in Bandung]]\nBandung can be accessed by highways from Jakarta. An intercity toll highway called [[Cipularang Toll Road]], connecting [[Jakarta]], [[Karawang]], [[Purwakarta]], Padalarang and Bandung, was completed in May 2005 and is the fastest way to reach Bandung from the capital by road. Driving time is about 1.5 hours on average. There are three other options: the Puncak route (Jakarta-[[Cianjur]]/[[Sukabumi]]-Bandung), Purwakarta route (Jakarta-Cikampek-Purwakarta-Cikalong Wetan-Padalarang-Cimahi-Bandung) and the Subang route (Jakarta-[[Cikampek]]-[[Subang, Indonesia|Subang]]-[[Lembang]]-Bandung). From cities further east ([[Cirebon]], [[Tasikmalaya]] and [[Central Java]] province), Bandung can be accessed through the main provincial road. [[Indonesian National Route 3]] links Bandung with the rest of Java towards [[Cilegon]] and Ketapang ([[Banyuwangi]]).\n\nThe [[Pasupati Bridge]]  was built to relieve traffic congestion in the city for east-west transport. The {{convert|2.8|km|1|adj=on}} [[cable-stayed bridge]] lies through the Cikapundung Valley. It is {{convert|30|to|60|m|ft|abbr=off}} wide and, after extensive delays, it was finally completed in June 2005, following financial investment from [[Kuwait]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kuwait Investasikan 1,5 Milyar Dollar AS di Indonesia|trans-title=Kuwait invested USD 1.5 billion in Indonesia|url=http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0209/14/ekonomi/kuwa14.htm|work=Kompas|language=Indonesian|date=14 October 2002|accessdate=23 August 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311083734/http://www.kompas.com/kompas-cetak/0209/14/ekonomi/kuwa14.htm|archivedate=11 March 2007}}</ref> The bridge is part of Bandung's comprehensive inner-city highways plan.\n\n[[Taxicab|Taxis]] and [[mobile apps]] transport are widely available. The primary means of public transportation is by ''[[Share taxi#Indonesia|angkot]]'' minibuses (from ''angkutan'', \"transportation\" and ''kota'', \"city\"); ''angkot'' are privately operated and serve multiple routes throughout the city, and although cheap, they are considered basic and uncomfortable.<ref>[http://www.bandung.world-guides.com/bandung_travel.html Bandung Transport and Car Rental: Bandung, West Java, Indonesia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> To find exact angkot routes, passengers may look for information available through the drivers or at terminals. [[Perum DAMRI|''DAMRI'']] buses operate on longer high capacity routes. \n\nBandung has two intercity bus terminals: Leuwipanjang, serving buses from the west, and Cicaheum, serving buses from the east. Both are at full capacity and are to be replaced by a new terminal at Gedebage on {{convert|15|ha}} land, after which the old terminals will function as inner-city terminals. The new terminal will be located next to the Gedebage railway station near Gedebage container dry port.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/147232|title=Bappeda Targetkan Studi Kelaikan Terminal Gedebage Selesai Tahun Ini|work=Pikiran Rakyat|date=2 June 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324152413/http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/147232|archivedate=24 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Air===\nBandung [[Husein Sastranegara International Airport]] serves direct domestic flights to [[Batam]], [[Pekanbaru]], [[Medan]], [[Bandar Lampung]], [[Surabaya]], [[Yogyakarta]], [[Semarang]], [[Banjarmasin]], [[Makassar]], and also international services to/from [[Kuala Lumpur]] and [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]. The airport is located near the Dirgantara aerospace complex and Dirgantara Fairground. The [[Kertajati International Airport]] in Majalengka Regency is built to replace the Husein Sastranegara Airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2017/07/24/056893823/Angkasa-Pura-II-Named-Kertajati-Airport-Operator|title=Angkasa Pura II Named Kertajati Airport Operator|newspaper=Tempo|accessdate=2017-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jakartaglobe.id/corporate-news/angkasa-pura-ii-operate-kertajati-west-javas-biggest-airport|title=Angkasa Pura II to Operate Kertajati, West Java's Biggest Airport|newspaper=Jakarta Globe|accessdate=2017-07-24|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725153232/http://jakartaglobe.id/corporate-news/angkasa-pura-ii-operate-kertajati-west-javas-biggest-airport/|archivedate=25 July 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Railway===\nBandung has two large railway stations, [[Bandung Station|Bandung]] and [[Kiaracondong Station]]s. Other smaller stations are Cimindi, Andir, [[Ciroyom Station|Ciroyom]], Cikudapateuh, and Gedebage Stations (only for freight service). Railway lines connect Bandung to [[Cianjur]], [[Jakarta]], [[Purwakarta]], [[Bekasi]], [[Karawang]], and [[Cikampek]] to the west, and [[Surabaya]], [[Malang]], [[Yogyakarta]], and [[Solo, Central Java|Solo]] to the east. It is also a major means of transportation for people living in the suburban areas of [[Cimahi]], Padalarang, Rancaekek, Cicalengka, and Cileunyi. In 2012, Bandung Commuter Train phase-1 was scheduled to be built to connect Padalarang, [[Cimahi]], Bandung, and Cicalengka with 13 Trans Metro Bandung bus corridors to serve as feeders. Phase-2 will connect Cicalengka to Jatinangor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://koran-jakarta.com/index.php/detail/view01/77287 |title=Transportasi Kota \u2013 KRL Komuter Bandung Dibangun |work=Koran Jakarta |date=29 November 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426041920/http://koran-jakarta.com/index.php/detail/view01/77287 |archivedate=26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Current and future development===\nThirty-two bus shelters for Trans Metro Bandung (similar to [[TransJakarta]]) along Jalan Soekarno-Hatta were finished in August 2011 at the cost of Rp 13.1 billion ($1.54 million). Thirty additional buses joined the existing operation of ten buses after all the shelters were finished.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/152679|title=Shelter Trans Metro Bandung Ditargetkan Rampung Akhir Agustus 2011|work=Pikiran Rakyat|date=21 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324153313/http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/152679|archivedate=24 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2011, [[Perum DAMRI]] launched two buses on the Cibiru-Kebon Kelapa especially for female passengers only with female drivers.<ref>[http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/06/21/bandung-introduces-women-only-buses.html Bandung introduces women-only buses | The Jakarta Post<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 2011, [[Jusuf Kalla]] announced that he would like to build a [[monorail]] in Bandung with a value of Rp 4 trillion ($470 million).<ref>[http://www.tribunnews.com/2011/08/05/jusuf-kalla-siapkan-rp-4-triliun-untuk-monorel-bandung Jusuf Kalla Siapkan Rp 4 Triliun untuk Monorel Bandung - Tribunnews.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n{{As of|2012|04}}, a cable car project 'Bandung Skybridge' to connect Pasteur (Cihampelas) to Sabuga (Taman Sari) was said to be 90% complete and awaiting legal authorisation to operate.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/185342 |title=\"Bandung Skybridge\" akan Direalisasikan |work=Pikiran Rakyat |date=20 April 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422041745/http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/node/185342 |archivedate=22 April 2012}}</ref> However, {{As of|2016|lc=y}}, the project has still to be realised. To ease Cihampelas traffic congestion, the city mayor, Ridwan Kamil inaugurated a skywalk for pedestrians only from Cihampelas to Tamansari on 4 February 2017. The skywalk, named Teras Cihampelas, was built with a budget of Rp 45 billion.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saokani|first1=Kukuh|title=Skywalk Cihampelas Bandung Hadir untuk Manjakan Pejalan Kaki|url=http://regional.liputan6.com/read/2847254/skywalk-cihampelas-bandung-hadir-untuk-manjakan-pejalan-kaki|accessdate=18 March 2017|work=liputan6.com|date=5 February 2017|language=id}}</ref> Vehicles will be able to be parked at Tamansari.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jabar.tribunnews.com/2014/02/08/bandung-skywalk-tahap-pertama-dibangun-di-cihampelas |title=Bandung Skywalk Tahap Pertama Dibangun di Cihampelas |date=8 February 2014}}</ref> The city has also announced an intention to build LRT (Light Rail Transit).\n\n==Education==\n[[File:ITB 1.jpg|thumb|right|[[Bandung Institute of Technology]]]]\nBandung has nearly 50 higher educational institutions and is among the most popular destinations for education in Indonesia. There are hundreds of public and private schools in the city and several state-funded and administered Junior High Schools (SMP Negeri) and State High Schools (SMA Negeri). At least sixteen universities\u2014three of which are state-owned\u2014and 45 [[professional schools]] are scattered across the city. Education from social sciences and technology to tourism education can be found at one of these universities.\n\nAmong the universities located in Bandung include [[Bandung Institute of Technology]] (''Institut Teknologi Bandung'', ITB), [[Universitas Padjadjaran]] (Padjadjaran University), [[National Institute of Technology (Indonesia)]] (Institut Teknologi Nasional), [[Parahyangan Catholic University]], [[Universitas Islam Bandung]], (Bandung Islamic University), [[Maranatha Christian University|Universitas Kristen Maranatha]] (Maranatha Christian University), Universitas Islam Nusantara (Nusantara Islamic University), [[Universitas Pendidikan Indonesia]] (Indonesia University of Education), Universitas Islam Negeri Sunan Gunung Djati (Sunan Gunung Djati Islamic State University), Universitas Pasundan (Pasundan University), [[Institut Teknologi Telkom]] (Telkom Institute of Technology), Politeknik Negeri Bandung (Bandung State Polytechnic), and Sekolah Tinggi Pariwisata Bandung (Bandung Institute of Tourism), all being considered among the best universities in their respective fields of speciality in Indonesia. Established in 1920, ITB is Indonesia's oldest and most prestigious technical university. [[Universitas Pendidikan Indonesia]] (formerly IKIP Bandung, established in 1954) Universitas Komputer Indonesia (UNIKOM) is one of the first institutions of higher education established after Indonesian independence and is currently a leading education university in the country. [[Universitas Padjadjaran]] (established in 1956) is considered to be one of the best universities in the country in the fields of medicine, law, communication, and economics.\n\nInternational schools are also available in the city. They include the [[Bandung Alliance Intercultural School]], [[Bandung Independent School]], Bandung Japanese School, [[Bina Bangsa School]] Bandung, Bina Persada School, and Stamford School. In the north of Bandung, [[Bosscha Observatory]] is the only [[observatory]] in Indonesia. Construction of the observatory began in 1923 and was completed in 1928. In 1922, the first international publication from Bosscha Observatory was published, and in 1959, the observatory was absorbed as a part of the Department of [[Astronomy]] at the Bandung Institute of Technology).\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Empty section|date=February 2018}}\n{{Category see also|People from Bandung}}\n\n==Sister cities==\n{{refimprove section|date=July 2017}}\n{{Main|List of twin town and sister cities in Indonesia}}\nBandung has [[Town twinning|sister relationships]] with a number of towns worldwide:\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|\n\n*{{flagicon|USA}}  [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], United States<ref name=SCI>{{cite web|title=Fort Worth|url=http://www.sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Fort%20Worth,%20Texas|work=[[Sister Cities International]]|accessdate=11 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413144255/http://www.sister-cities.org/interactive-map/Fort%20Worth,%20Texas|archive-date=13 April 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Hamamatsu]], Japan\n*{{flagicon|KOR}} [[Suwon]], South Korea\n*{{flagicon|PRC}} [[Hangzhou]], China\n*{{flagicon|PRC}} [[Liuzhou]], China\n*{{flagicon|PRC}} [[Yingkou]], China\n*{{flagicon|KAZ}} [[Almaty]], Kazakhstan\n*{{flagicon|PHL}} [[Cotabato City]], Philippines\n*{{flagicon|THA}} [[Udon Thani]], Thailand\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Braunschweig]], Germany<ref name=\"Braunschweig twinnings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.braunschweig.de/kultur_tourismus/stadtportraet/partnerstaedte/index.html|title=Braunschweigs Partner und Freundschaftsst\u00e4dte|accessdate = 2013-08-07|work=Stadt Braunschweig [City of Braunschweig]|language=German|trans-title=Braunschweig \u2013 Partner and Friendship Cities|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201122754/http://www.braunschweig.de/kultur_tourismus/stadtportraet/partnerstaedte/partner_freundschaftsstaedte.html|archivedate=2012-12-01}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|MAS}} [[Kuantan]], Malaysia\n*{{flagicon|MAS}} [[Kuching]], Malaysia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bandungkita.id/2019/09/21/sarawak-malaysia-jajaki-kerjasama-sister-city-dengan-kota-bandung/|title=Sarawak Malaysia Jajaki Kerjasama Sister City dengan Kota Bandung|trans-title=Sarawak Malaysia Establish Sister City Co-operation with Bandung City|author=M Zezen Zainal M|language=Indonesian|publisher=Bandung Kita|date=21 September 2019|accessdate=26 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926030359/https://bandungkita.id/2019/09/21/sarawak-malaysia-jajaki-kerjasama-sister-city-dengan-kota-bandung/|archivedate=26 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.galamedianews.com/bandung-raya/234505/sarawak-malaysia-ajak-kota-bandung-jadi-sister-city.html|title=Sarawak Malaysia Ajak Kota Bandung Jadi Sister City|trans-title=Sarawak Malaysia Invites Bandung City To Become Sister City|author=Brilliant Awal|language=Indonesian|publisher=Gala Media News|date=21 September 2019|accessdate=26 September 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926030659/http://www.galamedianews.com/bandung-raya/234505/sarawak-malaysia-ajak-kota-bandung-jadi-sister-city.html|archivedate=26 September 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|MAS}} [[Petaling Jaya]], Malaysia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starproperty.my/PropertyScene/TheStarOnlineHighlightBox/24106/0/0 |title=A second sister city for PJ |work=starproperty.my |accessdate=2012-08-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811212547/http://www.starproperty.my/PropertyScene/TheStarOnlineHighlightBox/24106/0/0 |archivedate=11 August 2012 }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|INA}} [[Pekanbaru]], Indonesia\n*{{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Namur]], Belgium<ref>[http://m.antaranews.com/en/news/113008/namur-bandung-ink-sister-city-partnership \"Namur, Bandung ink sister-city partnership\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Brunei}} [[Tutong (town)|Pekan Tutong]], [[Brunei Darussalam]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n{{Commons category|Bandung}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Bandung}}\n* [http://bandung.go.id The official website of Bandung Government]\n* [http://yourbandung.com/ Your Bandung]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{West Java}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles related to Bandung\n| list  = \n{{Most populous cities in Indonesia}}\n{{Largest Cities in Southeast Asia}}\n{{Largest cities of Indonesia}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bandung| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Populated places in West Java]]\n[[Category:Provincial capitals in Indonesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bandung\n| official_name                   = City of Bandung<br>{{nobold|''Kota Bandung''}}\n| settlement_type      = [[List of regencies and cities of Indonesia|City]]\n| translit_lang1       = Other\n| translit_lang1_type1 = [[Sundanese alphabet|Sundanese]]\n| translit_lang1_info1 = {{Sund|\u1b8a\u1ba7\u1b92 \u1b98\u1b94\u1baa\u1b93\u1ba5\u1b80}}\n| image_skyline                = Montage of Bandung.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise, from top: [[Gedung Sate]], [[Grand Mosque of Bandung]], Bandung at night, [[Pasupati Bridge]], [[Merdeka Building]]\n| image_flag                      = Municipal Flag of Bandung, Indonesia.svg\n| image_shield                    = Lambang Kota Bandung.svg\n| nicknames                       = ''Kota Kembang'' (City of Flowers)<br/>''Parijs van Java'' ([[Dutch language|Dutch]]) (Paris of Java)\n| motto                      